name: NA
notes: Entered Oct 2017. The AAMU herbarium houses vascular, and eventually, nonvascular plants of Alabama, W.B. Bankhead National Forest and surrounding states. Vouchers are collected in areas where forestry students work, while they are attending AAMU. Collections will include thesis and dissertation specimens from research sites, collections submitted by professors/dendrology, forest management, taxonomy, and silviculture students, and donated specimens from the public at large. The herbarium will be accessible to individuals, by appointment, Monday – Friday, during the academic school year.

name: NA
section: A. M. B. National Mycological Herbarium
notes: Entered Apr 2009. The Associazione Micologica Bresadola was founded in Trento, 7 December 1957. It was originally called "Gruppo Micologico G. Bresadola". This name derives from the Abbot Giacomo Bresadola, one of the most important mycologists. In 1987 the name was changed to "Associazione Micologica Bresadola". The aim of the Association is to bring together people who are interested in mycology and conservation of fungi. The Association carries on intense editorial, scientific, legislative and local activities. It cooperates with State, regions, and institutes on mycological subjects. The Association's Mycological Study Center administrates of the Bresadola Mycological Library; creation of a scientific data bank on census and indexing of fungal speciesand maintenance of a mycological herbarium and data bank for toxicological problems. The Association's Library contains about 2,200 books and 100 periodicals. The list of the books and the periodicals of the library is avaiable for download at the webiste. file The library contains also older literature including "Nova Plantarum Genera", 1729, by P.A. Micheli ( 234 pp., Firenze).

name: NA
notes: The Herbarium of the Arkansas Natural Heritage Commission consists primarily of specimens collected in the course of statewide ecological and biological inventory work conducted by the Arkansas Natural Heritage Program. Many of the specimens represent species that are rare in the state or were collected from rare or unusual habitats. The goals of the collection are 1) to provide a reference collection for work performed by Natural Heritage Commission staff and their conservation partners, 2) to house voucher specimens for rare plant records in the database of the Arkansas Natural Heritage Program, and 3) to voucher plants of ecologically sensitive or otherwise significant lands, including those contained within the State's System of Natural Areas. While most specimens are from Arkansas, special care is being made to assemble a collection of plants from surrounding states that are not presently known in Arkansas but are likely to be found there. The herbarium has new custom-built housing, with accompanying lab and research rooms, Compactor units were installed in late 2016.

citation: Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin (2017). Herbarium Berolinense, Berlin (B). Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/dlwwhz accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
rightsholder: Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin
organization: Botanischer Garten und Botanisches Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Zentraleinrichtung der Freien Universität Berlin
geography: Worldwide, especially central Europe, Mediterranean area, southwestern Asia, Africa, Cuba, and South America
exchange: Angiosperms of Europe, especially southeastern part; mosses, lichens, and fungi
notes: Updated Jan 2017 (staff update). Specimens of B-W (Herbarium Willdenow) not sent on loan, but photographs provided. Herbarium destroyed by fire in 1943 except B-W, type material of selected angiosperms, pteridophytes, fungi p.p. (Uredineae and fungi imperfecti), and special collections (cf. Englera 7: 219-252. 1987 (http://www.bgbm.org/en/herbarium). Special collections of fruits and seeds, gymnosperm cones, spirit-preserved material, wood, fossils, and plant remains from Egyptian tombs.
incorporated herbaria: DUSS (6000 specimens) in 1998;BHU (270 000 specimens) in 1993;KOELN (25 000 lichens) in 2005;BSB (15 000 specimens) in 2005

name: NA
organization: Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales "Bernardino Rivadavia"
geography: Argentina, the Neotropics, and the Southern Hemisphere
exchange: Argentine dicotyledons, bryophytes, algae, and lichens; fossil plants; Argentine fossil diatoms
notes: Updated Sep 2016. (major update). Shipment of botanical specimens should be sent by regular mail, i.e. not by private couriers (such as FedEx, DHL and so on). BA contains more than 320000 specimens: vascular plants (242300 specimens including 1000 types), algae (4300), fungi (700), lichens (1500), bryophytes (44000), actuopalinology (3200), paleopalynology (6900), and fossil plants (13800 including 140 types). Ministry of Culture and Education, Secretary of Science and Technology.
incorporated herbaria: BACP: 20000 specimens (in 2004), former Centro de Estudios Farmacológicos y Botánicos;BUEN: 8000 specimens (in 2003), former Administración de Parques Nacionales;Flora criptogámica Fueguina CONICET, former Centro de Investigación de Biología Marina (CIBIMA)
associatedHerbaria: <Associated universities:> Universidad de Buenos Aires. Universidad de La Plata. Cornell University, Ithaca, New York, U.S.A.

name: NA
citation: Bennett B, Sinou C (2017). Bruce Bennett Herbarium (BABY). Version 2.0. Consortium of Pacific Northwest Herbaria. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.5886/cp1vgz accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
geography: Yukon Territory; Beringian and Circumboreal; Alaska, British Columbia, Manitoba, Ontario, Nunavut,  and Northwest Territories
notes: B.A. Bennett Herbarium contains only Vascular Plants. With more than 5400 Yukon specimens it is one of the largest and most comprehensive collections of vascular plants from Yukon. Visiting researchers and students are encouraged to use the herbaria. The library includes all significant northern floras including floras of Russian, Scandinavia, Europe, Canada, and the Pacific Northwest. Additional resources include over 4000 reprints primarily of literature relevant to the Yukon flora, including many historical accounts. Significant exchanges are currently made with UBC, ALA, CAN, DAO and to a lesser extent ALTA, ETST, UAAH, V, and WTU.

name: NA
organization: Department of Higher Education, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan
geography: The primary focus is Waziristan, Pakistan, and adjacent areas
exchange: Vascular plants of Bannu and Kark
notes: BANNU was established to promote scientific study of the Wasiristan's flora, both its taxonomic diversity and its use, particularly medicinal use, by local people. There is no existing flora of Waziristan and few specimens from the Waziristan in other herbaria. Records will be shared via OpenHerbarium (http://www.openherbarium.org) starting in the summer of 2019.

name: NA
organization: National Science and Technology Development Agency
branch: National Center for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology
notes: Updated Jan 2013 (staff update). Formerly listed under BANGKOK  Description of the fungus herbarium: The BIOTEC Fungal Herbarium was established in 1996 and was registered with Index Herbariorum in 2003. The herbarium has been housed in a purpose-built temperature/humidity controlled facility since 2003. The facility holds 40+ type specimens. Of the 20000+ specimens almost half represent insect fungi. Other major groups include Basidiomycetes (especially Marasmius and Mycena and allied genera) and Xylariales.,,  Despcription of the plant herbarium: The BIOTEC Plant Herbarium is managed by the Ecology and Geo-informatics Lab, and specializes in storing and distributing voucher specimens from the biodiversity research plots established by the Lab. Its main plot is the 30-ha forest dynamics plot in Khao Yai National Park. Voucher specimens from other research projects within BIOTEC and outside collaborators are also stored.

name: NA
notes: Entered Jul 2016. The foci of the University of Malakand Botanic Garden and Herbarium are 1) conservation of the local flora both in- and ex-situ; 2) development of a herbarium emphasizing local species; 3) monographic study of local species, particularly those of high value medicinal plants; 4) DNA/Protein genotyping with an emphasis on local species; 5) tissue culture of rare local species to support their conservation and multiplication. The herbarium currently has about 2000 dry specimens from different localities in the Malakand division, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan. More than 60% of the plants are endemic to Malakand division and acclimated to the environmental conditions of the botanic garden.

name: NA
notes: The library of the Institut de France in Paris holds two important herbaria bound in separate folio volumes. They were originally part of the collection of Johannes Burman (1706-1779) and his son Nicolaas Laurens Burman (1734-1793) which was acquired by Benjamin Delessert (1773-1847) in 1801 (see Wijnands et al., 2017). Delessert’s herbarium came to the City of Geneva in 1869 while his library went to the Institut de France. The main Burman herbarium is now incorporated in the Pre-Linnaean herbarium in Geneva (now G-PREL). However, two bound herbarium volumes were treated as part of the Delessert manuscripts and given to the Institut de France. The first of these contains material from Ceylon collected by Paul Hermann (1646-1695) which was the main basis of Johannes Burman’s Thesaurus Zeylanicus. Lourteig (1966) has provided a detailed catalogue of this herbarium (now BIF-CEYL). The second herbarium volume contains material collected by Carl Linnæus (1707-1778) during his Lapland journey in 1732. The specimens in this volume were annotated by Linnæus with the corresponding number of each species in his Flora Lapponica (1737) (see Jarvis, 2007). Jarvis & Jonsell (2003) have provided a detailed catalogue of this herbarium (now BIF-LAPP). [Compiled by M.W. Callmander and C. Jarvis, Apr. 2019]
incorporated herbaria: BIF-CEYL (Herbier de Ceylan collected by Hermann; Ms 973 Res, 213 specimens on 171 pages);BIF-LAPP (Herbier de Laponie collected by Linnaeus; Ms 3912 Res, 379 specimens on 155 pages)

name: NA
organization: Universidade Federal do Oeste da Bahia
notes: Entered Dec 2017. The herbarium BRBA is young, however is the unique collection located in the west of Bahia state. The west of Bahia is covered by a great extension of Cerrado vegation. The BRBA herbarium has almost 90% of its collection from closest areas in distinct physiognomies of this vegetation. Informatization and digitalization of all especimens are avaliable. We are in collaboration and we have a support of Jardim Botânico do Rio de Janeiro (JBRJ). Our system of curatorship is associated with JABOT. More information about BRBA is listed: Angiosperms correspond to 93.9% of all collection; Around 42% are determinated until species level; The more representative family is Leguminosae (1207 specimens), the second Malpighiaceae (171 specimens); In addition to Bahia there are plants from 19 others Brazilian states.   We don’t have a specific and specialized staff beyond the curator, the activities of the herbarium are working with students and volunteers.

geography: île de La Réunion (Reunion island) ; îles Eparses (Scattered islands)
notes: Updated Nov 2018 (specimen total). Herbaria of Reunion island and of the Scattered Islands are hosted within the CBNM based in Reunion island. They contain samples of terrestrial vascular plants collected in different islands of the western Indian Ocean: Reunion, Europa, Juan de Nova, Glorioso and Tromelin. Among these are 4936 specimens from Reunion Island and 2007 from the Scattered Islands. Formal partnerships were established in 2014 with the National Museum of Natural History (Paris, France) and with the Missouri Botanical Garden (Saint Louis, USA). These two herbaria are completed by samples preserved in alcohol, by seed banks and by a collection in silica gel. Since July 2016, data from the herbarium of the Scattered Islands are available online on Tropicos® (search by typing 'CBNM' in the name of Senior Collector).

department: Núcleo de Gestão em Biodiversidade e Saúde - NGBS (Management Center for Biodiversity and Health)
section: Coleção Botânica de Plantas Medicinais (Botanical Collection of Medicinal Plants)
exchange: Angiosperm (exclusively medicinal plants with tradicional/cientifical uses registered)
notes: Entered Jan 2019. The Botanical Collection of Medicinal Plants, CBPM, was established with the support from the Institute of Pharmaceutical Technology (Farmanguinhos) / Fiocruz. It aims to ensure the botanical identification and traceability of plant species of medical interest in order to facilitate secure access and rational use of medicinal plants and herbal medicines, promoting the sustainable use of biodiversity and the development of Science, Techonology & Inovation projects related to drugs from plant origin, in accordance with the precepts of the National Policy of Medical Plants and Herbal Medicines (Política Nacional de Plantas Medicinais e Fitoterápicos - PNPMF). The herbarium is registered in the Brazilian Herbaria Network formed from the "Herbaria Comission" of Brazil Botanical Society (Sociedade Botânica do Brasil - SBB) and is part of the Agroecological Platform of Phytomedicine (Plataforma Agroecológica de Fitomedicamentos -PAF) from the Management Center for Biodiversity and Health (Núcleo de Gestão em Biodiversidade e Saúde - NGBS) - Farmanguinhos / Fiocruz. The CBPM is dedicated to collecting, georeferencing, storage, exchange, preservation and botanical identification of medicinal plants, as well as providing advisory services in the areas of botany, ethnobotany and pharmacobotany to meet the institutions whose projects are registered in the PAF.
associatedHerbaria: Instituto de Pesquisas Jardim Botânico do Rio de Janeiro - JBRJ (Rio de Janeiro Botanical Garden Institute - JBRJ)

organization: Craveri Civic Museum of Natural History
notes: Entered Jan 2017. The herbarium was established by Bra native Federico Craven, co-founder of the museum, who between 1859 and 1880 collected and determined 622 species of vascular plants (862 specimens) mainly coming from the immediate surroundings of his town. To it were added other collections of which the most important are as follows: F. Rota (1950 specimens.), and G. Abba (450 specimens). This material is kept in special drawers and periodically subjected to fumigation. Much of the herbarium is being cataloged, to allow for rapid on-line consultation of specific data collection and determination of each artifact. The herbarium contains 300 specimens of lichens, 552 specimens of wood, a spermatoteca collection of 350, and 300 succulent plants.

name: NA
organization: Dr. Charles F. and Wilhelmina Husser Clark Herbarium
notes: Updated Jan 2016 (staff update). The Clark Herbarium serves as a reference library to the plant diversity and changes of Southern California. With almost 10,000 specimens, the Clark Herbarium includes dry botanical mounts, most of which were collected from the Riverside region and surrounding counties by J. C. Roos and other botanists between 1920 and 1990. A small collection of lichens and fungi was assembled during the 1930s by Edmund C. Jaeger, and was later donated to the Museum during his tenure as Curator of Plants. All these materials now represent an important database describing the distribution of native plant species in the southwestern U.S., which is now a vastly altered environmental setting.

name: NA
geography: Western Ghats, Eastern Ghats & Andaman and Nicobar Islands
notes: Entered Apr 2011.   The herbarium is currently arranged according to Bentham & Hooker's system, although a rearrangement based on APG-III has been initiated. Arya Vaidya Sala, Kottakkal has been maintaining a demonstration Garden of 8 acres with a live collection of more than thousand species of medicinal plants. These plants are collected from different parts of India, Andaman and Nicobar Islands, Malaysia, Nepal and other neighbouring countries. Rare species like <Utleria salicifolia>, <Janakiya arayalpatra>, <Decalepis hamiltonii>, <Rauvolfia serpentina>, <Embelia ribes>, <Coscinium fenestratum> etc. are conserved here. The main objective of this garden is to create awareness among the public on our medicinal plant wealth and the need for conserving the floristic diversity.
associatedHerbaria: Arya Vaidya Sala Herb Garden Herb Garden, Arya Vaidya Sala, Kottakkal Malappuram-676 503, KERALA, INDIA

name: NA
geography: Worldwide, especially Portugal and tropical Africa
notes: Updated Jan 2010. Since 1879 the Herbarium of the Department of Botany of the University of Coimbra, Portugal (COI), has owned the Herbarium of the german (Saxonian) Henrich Moritz Willkomm, Professor at Prague University and a specialist on the flora of the Iberian Peninsula. This collection was bought to Willkomm and contains vascular and non-vascular plants of the Mediterranean area and the Macaronesian Islands and includes c. 10.000 species and over 30.000 specimens. The specimens were collected by Willkomm himself and other relevant botanical collectors of the time e.g., Bourgeau, Orphanides, Sieber, Lange, Loscos, Boissier, Reuter, Lagasca, Cavanilles. It was the basis for Willkomm & Lange's Prodromus Florae Hispanicae (1861-1880), the first comprehensive Flora of most of the Iberian Peninsula - only now being superseded by the Flora iberica (Castroviejo et al., 1986-, Madrid) - and contains many type specimens of Iberian taxa. Not all Willkomm specimens are at COI and some are scattered in other institutes. But this is by far the largest assemblage of his material and he regarded it as his core collection which, as a whole he sold to Júlio Henriques, the founder of COI. Specimens in Willkomm Herbarium not sent on loan.

notes: Updated March 2018 (general update). CSH founded in 2005, opened in April 2010, the herabrium covered 1,560 square metres at the basement in Shanghai Chenshan Plant Science Research, CAS, and can ultimately hold about 1,000,000 dried specimens.  Up to 2018, CSH totally hold 150,000 specimens, 70% of them had been digitized. CSH mainly collects vascular plants in East Asia, and now collected plentiful of specimens from East China Sea islands, Shanghai and East China region (including Anhui, Fujian, Jiangsu, Jiangxi, Shandong and Zhejiang), and also collected invasive plants in China. For some groups, like Polypodiaceae, Lepisorus, Dennstaedtiaceae, Microlepia and Tectariaceae in ferns, Aristolochiaceae, Begoniaceae, Celastraceae, Fagaceae, Machilus (Lauraceae), Salvia (Lamiaceae), CSH extended the range to East Asia and East Africa.

notes: Entered Apr 2017. The primary goal of herbarium of the University of Antananarivo is the teaching of plant identification techniques at the academic level. Nearly all of the specimens stored at the herbarium have been collected by students preparing their degrees (from Master or PhD fieldwork) or by the research team of the DBEV (plant biology departement)during their fieldwork. These specimens come often from remote areas, as botanical studies carried out at this department are usually located in sites where the flora remains understudied. Many of the specimens stored at the DBEV herbarium are unique and rarely have duplicates at other herbaria around the world.

name: NA
notes: DSUM has been transferred to BHSC. The Dakota State University Herbarium was originally housed in a small rural university in south central South Dakota. The collection focused on plants collected regionally in the glacial prairie-pothole lake region of transition tall grass-short grass prairie of the Northern Great Plains In addition to serving as a resource for teaching, the herbarium was a temporal and spatial repository of plants collected periodically during the rapid conversion of native prairie to cropland during the 20th Century. This conversion accelerated during the century and continues today. A very small diminishing fraction of native prairie remains. Because of the regional emphasis of the collections, the herbarium served as a resource to allow research on species composition and distribution regionally as affected by global warming and global climate change.

name: NA
notes: Updated Apr 2017 (general update).  The University of Dundee’s Herbarium contains many thousands of plant specimens, including the largest public collection of Angus flora, as well as comparative specimens from other parts of Scotland. It also has some more exotic plants from further afield, such as a fascinating 19th century collection of Darjeeling Ferns. The Herbarium was created by Patrick Geddes, the first Professor of Botany at what was then University College Dundee. Lack of resources forced Geddes to abandon his work on the collection, and only a few of the specimens that came to the University during his time survive today. The Herbarium does, however, contain many plant specimens from the 19th century, though these were acquired at a later date. Following the gift of the Corstorphine Collection to the University in 1944, a later Botany lecturer, Dr Hugh Ingram, recommenced the active collection of herbarium specimens during the latter half of the 20th century. Thanks to this activity and the addition of other important collections there are now approximately 15,000 specimens in the Herbarium.

name: NA
geography: Eastern Morocco (especially from the Oujda-Figuig-Midelt-Guercif area) and Saharan Morocco (especially from Foum zguid-Tata-Foum El Hissn area)
notes: Updated Feb 2015. ECWP herbarium is open to any researcher and amateur, by appointment, on request. However validation by the ECWP Operation Director is mandatory. The ECWP herbarium is located at ECWP headquarters in Missour, Morocco, in a building dedicated to botanical studies. Specimens are mounted on acid-free, archival paper (48 x 28 cm) and are stored in cardboard boxes, that are themselves in cabinets. 2300 Moroccan taxa are currently in the collection, including some types specimens. Many vouchers have been verified by Mohammed Ibn Tattou (Institut Scientifique de Rabat), one of the authors of the Flore pratique du Maroc. There is an Excel file list of identified specimens vouchers. A software dedicated to sample collection management is planned for 2015. ECWP also has a botanical bibliographical collection, specializing in south-west Mediterranean flora and habitats, that includes 200 books and monographs and >10000 pdf files (books, monographs, papers). There is a flora/fauna database in the production for over three years, including over 1400 recent phytosociological relevés

organization: The Everhart Museum of Natural History, Science & Art
notes: Entered Oct 2010. The Alfred Twining Herbarium is housed in two metal cabinets in the basement of the Everhart Museum. The specimens are mounted on herbarium sheets or are loose in folders which are enclosed in additional folders and are arranged in a family sequence used by Alfred Twining in his <Flora of Northeastern Pennsylvania> (1917). Most of the specimens were collected by Twining in the early twentieth centure prior to the publication of the flora. EMNH is the major repository for Twining specimens -- few are duplicated at PH. However, most, if not all, of the Glowenke specimens (from the 1930s) are duplicated in PH (summarized from an assessment of the herbarium by A. Schuyler). Supercedes EVMU.

geography: Important collections from forest protected areas (Ituri Forest, Réserve de Faune à Okapis, Virunga National Park, Itombwe Forest, Kabogo-Marungu-Mitoshi; and Salonga National Park.
notes: Entered May 2011. This herbarium is based in the Ituri Forest. It has been developed to be a herbarium of reference for research in biodiversity and plant conservation, flora and tropical botany, forest ecology studies of DR Congo protected areas.   The herbarium collection contains a number of endemic species and important collections of little-known areas of botanical diversity importance (Inselbergs and Edos (salines).   It is the only herbarium devoted to the study of the DR Congo protected areas flora, and has been active in updating and providing recent collections from DR Congo during the last two decades.   This herbarium is also active in developing a "National Strategic Plan for Plants Conservation" and working with IUCN for the Red Data Listing in DR Congo.

name: NA
notes: Updated Apr 2014. The Elizabeth Teter Lunn Herbarium is home to more than 5,000 plant specimens dating primarily from the turn of the twentieth century, with some being collected, purportedly, as early as 1848. Between the years 1895 and 1897. M.C. Jensen, a student and botanist, collected more than 80 specimens within the city of Lake Forest, IL, and added these to the College's collection. At present, student Victoria Jones is in the process of writing a proposal for Lake Forest College to pay more attention to the collection and thus salvage this one-of-a-kind herbarium. This proposal reflects Victoria's senior-thesis topic and all of the tedious curatorial work she has committed to for the past three years. Victoria is currently working alongside Gerould Wilhelm, the foremost vascular plant botanist of the Chicago Region, to observe truth and beauty in each specimen of the ETL Herbarium. The outcome will be Gerould Wilhelm's & Laura Rericha's brand new book, "Flora of the Chicago Region." This book will update Swink & Wilhelm's "Plants of the Chicago Region" (1994).  The majority of the collection contains specimens from Illinois Beach State Park (IBSP) collected by Elizabeth Teter Lunn (professor at Lake Forest College) between the 1950s and mid-1970s. Lunn's interest in collecting from IBSP was based on an earlier study tallying the park's flora during the 1900s. The result was the publication of her guidebook, "Plants of the Illinois Dunesland," completed in 1982 and published by The Illinois Dunesland Preservation Society.

name: NA
geography: Worldwide, especially Italy and Mediterranean area
notes: Updated Nov 2011. FI includes the following herbaria: General Herbarium, which incorporates Herbarium Centrale Italicum (~ 3 800 000 specimens) and to which belong Herbarium Libycum (15 000 specimens) and Herbarium Cryptogamicum (780 000 specimens); separate historical herbaria: Herbarium Webbianum (FI-W; 300 000 specimens), Herbarium Beccarianum-Malesia (FI-B; 16 000 specimens), Herbarium Beccari Palmae (FI-BP; 6700 specimens), and Herbarium Michelianum (FI-M; 18 366 specimens). The Botanical Section also includes historical herbaria such as A. Cesalpino, 16th century, M. Merini, 16th century, A. Coltellini, 18th century, and wax and gypsum plant models of 18th and 19th century. On September 22nd, 2009 the Pteridological Herbarium of Professor R.E.G. Pichi Sermolli (1912-2005) was incorporated. Professor Pichi Sermolli, a worldwide known pteridologist, left a rich herbarium of 25,000 specimens including much type material and a specialized library of 450 books and 7,000 reprints. Professor Pichi Sermolli's herbarium is referred to by us as FI-PS, since it is a special collection of FI. Any request should be sent to the usual address of FI:   This precious collection is available to all interested researchers and specialists after prior arrangement; due to the historical significance and uniqueness of the a collections, loan is possible only through digital images. it is now possible to consult the data base archive of the Herbarium Centrale Italicum (FI) for the Italian specimens. The data base gives the full scientific name, the occurrence of types, any reference to synonyms, floristic records, literature, etc. and the names of Italian regions the specimens come from. Obviously the archive is "in progress", in the sense that it will be regularly updated.  It is also possible to request loans of the specimens directly, clicking on "Loan request". The loan is made only to Institutions registered for the Index Herbariorum.   To consult this data base, go to the web address of the Natural History Museum of Florence www.msn.unifi.it, click on "Botanical Section Herbaria" http://parlatore.msn.unifi.it and then on HCI ITALY WEB.

name: NA
notes: The Department of Botany is one of the oldest departments in the University, being established in 1902. Prof. Shiv Ram Kashyap, who was the department head from 1912 to 1934, established a museum and herbarium. The herbarium’s holdings included plants from many regions, including China, Indonesia and Philippines, and its collection of liverworts and mosses was considered the largest in the subcontinent at that time. The collection grew to include several hundred specimens of algae, fungi, bryophytes, pteridophytes, gymnosperms and angiosperms but, when the University of the Punjab was established as a separate institution, most of the specimens were transferred there. The present museum and herbarium are named the Prof. Kashyap Museum and Dr. Sultan Ahmed Herbarium. Both are being actively developed.   The Department also has a botanic garden, Botanic Garden GCU, which was founded in 1912 and extends over 7 acres. It has long been recognized for the diversity of its holdings. It is home to Pakistan’s Botanic Gardens Network Secretariat.

notes: Updated Nov 2016 (Notes update). GH is fully integrated with A and AMES in the Harvard University Herbaria, but specimens from Gray Herbarium should be cited as GH. The 1 943 000 specimens in GH are included in the total given for the Harvard University Herbaria (listed under GH). The previously separate Harvard herbaria (A, AMES, ECON, FH, GH) were fully integrated in the 1980s and are now administered as a single unit. Although loans of vascular plants from the Harvard University Herbaria will include appropriate specimens from A, AMES, ECON, and GH, and also material from the New England Botanical Club Herbarium (NEBC), specimens cited in publications should use the standard abbreviations for each of those herbaria. Correspondence regarding specimens should not be sent to the separate institutions, but to huh-requests@oeb.harvard.edu. Work space can be provided for both long- and short-term visitors; written requests, especially for long-term visitors, should be sent to Michaela Schmull (mschmull@oeb.harvard.edu). Also available for study are 50 000 paleobotanical specimens, 33 000 specimens of wood, 38 000 microscope slides of wood, 15 000 slides of other plant parts in the Bailey-Wetmore Wood Collection (Aw), and 11 000 pollen slides.
incorporated herbaria: Boston Society of Natural History diatoms in FH, vascular plants in GH in 1941;non-Worcester County material of CUW in GH in 1985;WELC South American collections in GH in 1985;NEBC (251 850 specimens) in 1992 (but see separate entry for NEBC).
associatedHerbaria: <Associated garden:> Arnold Arboretum, The Arborway, Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts 02130; Robert E. Cook, Director; telephone: [1] 617/ 524-1718; fax: [1] 617/ 524-1418.

name: NA
notes: Updated Feb 2017 (staff update). The collections are recorded digitally in the IrisBG database, Botanical Garden Collection Management. Hoyt Arboretum and Herbarium is integral with the Portland Parks and Recreation (PPR) system. PPR manages 11,209 acres of parks with 7,593 acres being natural areas. PPR also employs ecologists and restoration biologists. I aspire to bring to PPR, Metro, Bureau of Environmental Services, Portland State U., and general public; through Hoyt Arboretum and Herbarium, access to our living collections and herbarium to create regional research opportunities as well as achieving greater taxonomic resolution in our parks natural areas. The Herbarium is creating invasive species "teaching voucher" collection for regional institution education programs. Hoyt Arboretum research library is available to the above institutions and the public.  450 archived tree species; 358 regional invasive teaching vouchers-and growing as invasive species vouchers are made. We have a target over 12,000 as we continue vouchering our arboretum-minimum 2 vouchers per species

notes: Somaliland is considered by the United Nations to be part of Somalia but it declared its independence in 1991 and has functioned separately since that time. HARG was started in 2016 to be a primary resource for research and education about Somaliland’s plants, fungi and plants. At present it houses only vascular plants. There is NO regular mail service in Somaliland; one can send items via DHL but it is expensive. Neither the herbarium nor the university can pay for DHL service. The herbarium does not as yet have an accumulation of specimens for exchange.

name: HDJF - Herbário Dendrológico Jeanine Felfili
citation: Luiz Mendonça Machado E (2019). HDJF - Herbário Dendrológico Jeanine Felfili. Version 1.57. Universidade Federal dos Vales do Jequitinhonha e Mucuri. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/jovi18 accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
organization: Universidade Federal dos Vales do Jequitinhonha e Mucuri
geography: Brazil, especially Minas Gerais; Cerrado (savanna); campos rupestres (rocky grasslands); Atlantic Forest (tropical rain forest and dry forest)
exchange: savanna; rocky grasslands; tropical rain forest; dry forest
notes: O herbário foi idealizado em 2006 pelos estudantes e docentes do Departamento de Engenharia Florestal da Universidade Federal dos Vales do Jequitinhonha e Mucuri com finalidade de subsidiar as disciplinas deste curso, oferecer suporte aos estudos de vegetação e consequentemente congregar coleções científicas da flora regional. Em 2011 o acervo tomou proporções consideráveis sendo necessárias melhorias na forma de armazenamento e novas estruturas e equipamentos foram adquiridos. Nesta época o herbário recebeu a denominação Herbário Dendrológico Jeanine Felfili, com a sigla oficial HDJF, bem como o reconhecimento oficial junto à Rede Brasileira de Herbários e ao Index Herbariorum. O acervo HDJF está dividido em três partes, a saber: material herborizado; xiloteca e carpoteca. Todo o acervo está condicionado em uma área física de 66 m², com projeto de expansão aguardando recursos financeiros para tanto. O acervo do HDJF está compilado em bando de dados e as suas exsicatas estão sendo digitalizadas a fim de serem disponibilizadas online. O HDJF está inserido na porção Meridional da Serra do Espinhaço, fitogeograficamente a região que apresenta um complexo mosaico de florestas estacionais e savana, com diversas fitofisonomias relativamente bem preservadas, sendo considerada área prioritária para conservação e investigação científica. Assim no acervo tem destaque para a flora regional com exemplares dos biomas Mata Atlântica e Cerrado, contudo há também representação de outros biomas como Amazônia e Caatinga, oriundos do programa de permutas de duplicatas e intercâmbio com outros herbários.
physical street address: Campus JK - Rodovia MGT 367 - Km 583, nº 5000

organization: Universidade do Estado de Mato Grosso
notes: This herbarium has been developed based on research collaborations with other herbaria such as KEW and RB. HERBAM participates in Brazilian projects about biodiversity studies such as BIONORTE (Biodiversity of the North of the Brazil), PPBIO (Biodiversity Brazilian Programm) ; REFLORA (repatriation of specimens KEW and Paris Museum); National Brazilian Forestry Inventory/IFN/SFB; Teles Pires river basin Dams. The herbarium staff consists of post graduate students and scholarship holder and specialist volunteers who have been contribuited species identifications, such as William Milliken, Daniela Zappi and others. Duplicates are sent to RB and KEW.

name: NA
notes: Updated Aug 2017 (large general update). Implanted in the 70s under the coordination of Normélia Cláudia de Vasconcelos, the Herbarium of the Federal University of Pará (HF), originally belonging to the Department of Pharmacy, was transferred to the research building of the Institute of Biological Sciences (ICB) and later to the annex building of the ICB where it is currently. It is mainly intended for didactic and pedagogical activities, mainly for undergraduate courses in Biological Sciences, but also receives material from collections of practical activities from other institutes. Teaching and extension projects, coordinated by UFPA botany teachers and with the participation of trainee students resulted in an increase in the number of exsicates, as well as the introduction of fruits, seeds (carpoteca) and flow! ers, deposited in alcohol for conservation. Currently, the herbarium has a collection of approximately 3,271 samples, belonging to 51 botanical orders and 151 families. As it has not yet been possible to catalog and update all the specimens (this procedure is being done with the help of students), we still do not know how many genera and species the herbarium has. At present, the curator of the Herbarium is the responsibility of Dra. Roberta Macedo Cerqueira (Systematics and Plant Ecology Laboratory), who assumed this commitment at the end of August 2016. After changing the Herbarium curator, the order data, families and genera began to be updated for the classifications adopted by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG), which considers both molecular, morphological and anatomical data among others for the taxonomic classification of plants (the classification system previously adopted in the herbarium was the Engler System).

name: NA
rightsholder: The Regents of the Organization for Tropical Studies
organization: Las Cruces Biological Station, Organization for Tropical Studies
exchange: Regional flora of southern and central Costa Rica
notes: Updated Mar 2011. The Luis Diego Gomez Herbarium is located at the Las Cruces Biological Station (8° 47' 7'' N, 82° 57' 32'' W), one of three field stations owned and operated by the Organization for Tropical Studies (OTS; www.ots.ac.cr) in Costa Rica. This is a nascent herbarium (inaugurated 2006) but a comprehensive collection of the regional flora of southern Costa Rica is well underway, and all specimens are scanned and uploaded to the herbarium website. The collecting is only ~1,400 km2 but spans an elevational gradient of 300 - 3200 m and a rainfall range from 1.5 - 5 m (see website for a map of collecting range). The herbarium is expanding at a rate of ~600-700 specimens per year.

name: NA
notes: Entered Jan 2012. The Herbarium of Mordovian State Nature Reserve was initially all stored in one plywood cabinet. The fungi, lichens and mosses were stored in thick paper bags in a special plywood box. Today the herbarium collections of vascular plants Mordovian State Nature Reserve has 3216 herbarium sheets in 7 wooden cabinets, each of which is divided into 10 chambers, arranged in two columns. The specimens are arranged in the Englerian system. Most of the herbarium collections were made within the reserve and in adjacent territories. The herbarium reflects the species diversity of flora in the west of Mordovia, with 756 species belonging to 377 genera and 99 families. The macrofungus herbarium has about 1500 specimens and includes about 400 species. It is stored in plastic ziplock bags enclosed in kraft paper bags and is located on the system, adopted in the 9th edition of "Ainsworth and Bisbsy's Dictionary of the fungi". There are about 100 specimens of mosses, and about 700 specimens of lichens stored in cardboard boxes.

notes: Updated Jan 2016 (staff update). NHM is located at the ENS (Teacher Training College). It has an area of 150 sq. m., with a computer equipment and a laboratory specialist responsible for the data base.  NHM collaborates at the regional level with IFAN (Senegal) and (Rabat, Morocco). At the international level, it cooperates with the The National Museum of Natural History of Paris and the Montpellier University Herbarium.  NHM is the first and the only herbarium in Mauritania. It is very young, and the inventory of plant species in the country is at its beginning and we have a lack of human .ressources and skills. The flora of Mauritania represents a transition between the tropical flora and Mediterranean flora, with many endemic western saharan species.

name: NA
notes: The Northwestern University in the Philippines is a pioneering academic institution in the Northern Luzon geared in conserving the natural heritage of the country. The northwestern Luzon is home to numerous endemic plants species and cannot be found elsewhere in the world, despite is harsh climatic condition, natural calamities and human exploitation that aggravated the degradation of natural plant habitats. The Philippines is among the Megadiversity countries in the world yet among the most critically endangered, placing it as a hotspot for conservation. The university established its botanic gardens to perform the international agenda of botanic gardens in conservation and to halt the loss of species in our region.  The herbarium Includes 2,200 species of living plant collections at the Systematic Gardens with 226 Families and 124 subfamilies of the kingdom Plantae. The living plant collection and herbarium collections are extensively used for plant taxonomy (APG III). Top universities in Manila (University of the Philippines Diliman, University of the Philippines Manila, University of Santo Tomas and the De La Salle University Dasmarinas Cavite) annually conduct taxonomy courses in the botanic gardens which is arranged according to family and in their latest phylogenetic treatment  The specimens are also sent to the different botanical institutions around the world for DNA barcoding and genomics.  All specimens are newly acquired and collected in the wild to represent Flora of the Island Luzon, Philippines.
associatedHerbaria: Northwestern University and Ecotourism Park and Botanical Garden(BGCI). Other sites: covering 5 national park of Region 1, Philippines

name: NA
notes: Nupélia herbarium currently has researchers as well as graduate students (UEM) and PIBIC fellows through CNPq and Araucaria Foundation, and volunteers and interns. The main objective of the collection is documenting the riparian flora, including surveys, taxonomic identification and dissemination for both the scientific and general communities, and to generate subsidies for ecological studies, conservation of biodiversity, land reclamation and sustainable development, particularly riparian areas of the Upper Paraná River floodplain. It is the database of various theses and dissertations related to floristic and phytosociological surveys and Phanerogams taxonomy. Functionally and structurally the herbarium is linked to Nupélia. It is in computerization phase and available online by the Biological Collections Network of Paraná-Taxonline State and splink the CRIA. The herbarium is located in Block G-80 and open for consultation by experts appointment with coordination.

name: NA
notes: Entered Feb 2014. The herbarium moved from Johannesburg to Nelspruit area during 1998. The herbarium building, which incorporates the library and an annex for mounting and freezing of specimens at Whyte Thorne, was inaugurated in Feb 2001. The herbarium has been privately owned and funded from inception in 1967. The Herbarium, Library and Garden are open to all bona-fide botanically motivated persons. Whyte Thorne Botanic Garden has been developed on the same property, consisting of 23 hectares of which six acres comprise the laid –out garden and nursery including a 900sq m shade house & 34sq m propagation house. WTBG is a privately sponsored botanic Garden with 8300 living plant accessions, 6500 living plant orchid accessions and 11990 seed accessions. Accession numbers are cross-referenced to herbarium material where appropriate. D. McMurtry collecting numbers currently stand at 15200 of which ±7500 pressed specimens are lodged at the Johannesburg Botanic Garden Herbarium, the rest in HSMC. Duplicates in PRE and BNRH. Specimens mostly from the four northern provinces of S.Af. but include Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Namibia, Tanzania, Kenya, St Helena, Reunion, Madagascar and Comores . Carpological Spirit material (mostly Orchidaceae) collections maintained.

section: Herbarium of University of Caxias do Sul
notes: Updated Jun 2015. The HUCS Herbarium is a collection located in the northeast region of the Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil. It includes specimens of different local ecosystems, mostly of Araucaria Forest and Grassland vegetation. Nowadays the herbarium directs its sampling activities in the recognition of the coastal plain vegetation. At the same time, it has developed environmental education actions along with the Botanical Garden of Caxias do Sul.

name: NA
branch: Facultad de Ciencias Básicas y Tecnologías
notes: HUQ HISTORY:  FOUNDERS: Germán Arbeláez Serna and María Cristina Vélez Nauer, professors of the Degree Program in Biology at the University of Quindío. This process was supported directly by SANTIAGO DIAZ PIEDRAHITA of the Herbarium COL. HUQ INVESTIGATORS: Carlos Alberto Agudelo H., María del Pilar Sepúlveda, Germán Darío Gómez M., Andrés Felipe Orozco C., Ana Lucía López G., Rocío Stella Suárez, Ricardo Elías Vega, Carlos Alberto López R., Paula Andrea Viveros , Johan Carvajal, Larri Álvarez, Juan Fernando Restrepo, Carlos Alonso Maya, Rigoberto Villa, Rodolfo López, Nodier Augusto Botero, Jaime Uribe Meléndez, Neyver Rivera, Martha Chacón, among others. Among the administrative staff stands out Edier Flórez Henao. PUBLICATIONS: HUQ researchers have published numerous publications (approximately 100) in journals such as Flora de Colombia (Asteraceae and Amaranthaceae), Caldasia (Amaranthaceae), Biological News, Novon, Catalogs (Flora de Antioquia and Flora de Venezuela), abstract books of scientific events, among others. Books on taxonomy of mosses, Euphorbiaceae, wax palm, flórulas of some localities, four volumes of the magazine Flora Andina, etc. There are also online publications such as the Amaranthaceae in Neotropical Flowering Plants at https://www.kew.org/science/tropamerica/neotropikey.htm. YOUNG RESEARCHERS: At least 10 young Colombians, biologists and graduates in Biology, funded by COLCIENCIAS have passed through HUQ and have developed studies on flora, palynology, taxonomy, ecology, among others. INTERNATIONAL TRAINERS: Several interns from Croatia, Slovenia, Portugal, Brazil and Austria have conducted training and learning about the Andean flora in HUQ. INTERNATIONAL NETWORKS: The HUQ belongs to the Latin American Association of Botany - ALB, through Carlos A. Agudelo has participated as a member of the Superior Council of the ALB between 2010 and 2018, is also part of the Colombian Herbarium Association - ACH, of which he was President between 1998 and 1999 with Carlos A. Agudelo and is linked to the Global Initiative project of plants to type the world types in JSTOR through Felipe Orozco. We also work in a network with researchers from the University of Luján and La Matanza, Argentina through a binational agreement. With Venezuelan researchers participated in the elaboration of the New Catalog of the Flora of Venezuela, through Carlos A. Agudelo Amaranthaceae was reviewed for that country. MASTERY IN SCIENCES VEGETABLE BIOLOGY: the HUQ collection, its literature and researchers were fundamental to propose the creation of the Master in 2002 before the Ministry of National Education of Colombia. Through this program 28 botanists have graduated and by 2018 there are 25 more active. SCIENTIFIC EVENTS: The HUQ staff has carried out numerous local, regional, national and international scientific events (symposiums, congresses), courses, workshops, forums, diplomas (Organic Agriculture, protected areas and medicinal plants (the latter led by Orozco C., being very successful), botanical expeditions, have participated in the Latin American congresses of Botany of the ALB such as Cartagena in Colombia 2002, Santo Domingo in Dominican Republic 2006, La Serena in Chile 2010 and Salvador de Bahia in Brazil in 2014. The same They prepare to attend the XII Congress of Quito, Ecuador in 2018. They are part of the organizers of the biology regional symposiums held biannually among teachers from UTP, U. de Caldas, UNISARC and UniQuindío.

name: HVAT - Herbário do Vale do Taquari
citation: Maria de Freitas E (2019). HVAT - Herbário do Vale do Taquari. Version 1.57. Universidade do Vale do Taquari - UNIVATES. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/cmo532 accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
rightsholder: HVAT - Herbário do Vale do Taquari
organization: University of  Vale do Taquari - Univates
notes: Updated Sep 2017 (name of the institution updated). The Herbarium of Vale do Taquari (HVAT Herbarium) is linked to the Museum of Natural Sciences of Centro Universitário Univates. The Museum has started its activities in 1995 with the formalization of an agreement with the city of Lajeado, when it installed the Botanical Garden of the city, with the objective to record the species existing in that space. With the closing of the agreement, the first name (Herbarium Lajeado Botanical Garden - HJBL) was replaced by HUNIVATES and later by the current name. Since then, the Herbarium has the legacy to support the documentation of regional plant diversity and the availability of this information to the scientific and general community. The herbarium is part of the Brazilian Network Herbarium and the Rio Grande do Sul Herbarium Network, and is connected to SpeciesLink network. The Herbarium of Vale do Taquari has also integrated INCT Virtual Herbarium of Flora and Fungi during the period of the project. The collection, organized according to the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group III system, is fully computerized using the software database Brahms and available online at SpeciesLink. The samplings are originated from 13 Brazilian states, being most of them from the southern of Brazil, representative two of the existing biomes in Rio Grande do Sul (Pampa and Atlantic Forest). Considering the phytoecological formations, the most representative is the species that make up the Deciduous Forest of the Atlantic Forest biome, plant formation where the region of your location is located. The records of the species are distributed in 177 families, being Orchidaceae the most representative, followed by Asteraceae, Poaceae, Fabaceae, among others. It should be noted that the species of the Orchidaceae family are well represented in the Herbarium, constituting one of the largest collections of this family in Rio Grande do Sul.
physical street address: Avenida Avelino Tallini, 171 Museu de Ciências Naturais Prédio 8

name: NA
notes: Although only several years passed from the establishment of our Herbarium but we have actively tried to collect and document Iranian plant specimens, especially vascular plants of two large families, Asteraceae (genus Artemisia) and Amaryllidaceae (genus Allium). What is remarkable about our activities is that beside each Herbarium voucher we tried to collect also seed or living material. Currently all these materials preserve under optimal conditions in herbarium cabinets (dried sheets), refrigerators and/or freezers (usually seeds) or under cultivation in our living collections (bulbous or rhizomatous plants). We devoted an extra code (IBRC code) than herbarium numbers to each specimen to link easily different types of collected material.   Hitherto, our team had more than 300 working days mission to throughout of Iran to collect both herbarium and living material of special Iranian flora. In parallel to our Center policy, we are going to raise continuously our collections inventories.   Recently, we decided to gradually digitize our determined and labeled sheets and put them available via internet. Interested researchers can see so far prepared specimens online via this internet address: http://ibrc.ir/index.aspx?fkeyid=&siteid=1&pageid=466&siteid=1
associatedHerbaria: Three Living collections: collection of around 650 Iranian Allium accessions, A research collection of about 350 rhizomatous and bulbous plants, several greenhouses

name: NA
organization: Macquarie University Indigenous Bioresources Research Group (IBRG)
notes: Entered Jan 2016.  This is a very small herbarium, managed and run only to provide a place to store specimens of ethnobotanical interest for a small scale research unit at Macquarie University. We have chosen to register an independent herbarium as publication for scholarly journals in this field requires unique records to be retained of all samples collected for testing. Consequently we have a lot of duplicate records, often from the same plant, many of which do not have floristic parts or other useful diagnostic features. These are not acceptable in other herbaria we have available to us.

name: NA
organization: Iranian Research Organization for Science and Technology (IROST)
notes: Entered May 2016. The Iranian Cryptogamic Herbarium currently contains mostly lichenized, lichenicolous fungi as well as wood inhabiting macrofungi. This collection has an estimated number of 2000 specimens mainly from Iran and some duplicates from around the world, with an emphasis on Caspian Hyrcanian mixed forests, Oak forests in Zagros Mountains, arid and semiarid steppes ecosystems. It is a fundamental resource for biological systematics and classification, diversity and conservation, biotechnological applications, biological monitoring, biodeterioration and bioremediation studies, climate change, ecology, and pharmaceutical bio-prospecting. The collection is a resource for academics, students, government, private organizations, and the public. The Biotechnology institute was established in 1980 and currently 22 scientific members from different disciplines of Biotechnology, Microbiology, Mycology and Lichenology were employed. The institute launched its first collection project "Culture collection for Research and Industry" with deposition of ca. 3000 bacterial and microbial strains including some fungi cultures collection. The collection is registered as PTCC in the World Federation of Culture Collection.  The Iranian Research Organization for Science and Technology (IROST) is a governmental organization, founded in 1980, with the aim of providing support to Iranian researchers, inventors and industrialists across the country. This organization provides valuable services in fulfilling the country's scientific, technical and engineering requirements through supporting applied and developmental research as well as developing new technologies by exploiting qualified experts and modern equipment and facilities.

name: NA
organization: Institute of the Industrial Ecology Problems of the North of Kola Science Center of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
notes: Updated Apr 2017 (specialty, correspondent, important collections updated).  There are three collections in the herbarium. The main collection contains vascular plants (1500 specimens), fungi (1600 specimens), lichens (500 specimens) and bryophytes (1320 specimens) from the Murmansk Region and other northern regions. Additionally, the Museum of Bacteria, Algae and Microfungi of the Kola Peninsula includes strains of bacteria (37), algae (200) and microfungi (395) isolated from soils (virgin and polluted by industrial emissions of the «Severonikel» and the «Pechenganikel» enterprises, of the aluminium plant, oil-contaminated), air and anthropogenically altered environment (apatite-nepheline ore, nepheline sands, circulating water of mining plant and others) of Kola Peninsula. Another special collection, Diatoms of the Euro-Arctic Region, includes specimens of diatom complexes from the sediments and biotopes from polytypic ancient and modern water bodies, periphyton and plankton of Euro-Arctic Region: Kola Peninsula (Imandra Lake, River Paz system, mountain lakes and rivers of Khibiny and Chuna-tundra massifs and others), Arkhangelsk region (River Pechora basin), lakes and streams of Novaya Zemlya Island, Svalbard archipelago, Barents, Norwegian, Greenland and Laptev’s Seas. This collection, founded in 1993, contains 150 different specimens (about 3700 slides). First volume of the Fungi Exsiccates from Murmansk Region issued in 2016. The present fascicule includes labels of 15 species: Amylostereum chailletii, Asterodon ferruginosus, Ceraceomyces serpens, Cerioporus mollis, Ceriporiopsis mucida, Clavaria fragilis, Laurilia sulcata, Laxitextum bicolor, Ramariopsis subtilis, Oxyporus populinus, Phellinus laevigatus, Sistotrema confluens, Skeletocutis stellae, Veluticeps abietina, Xanthoporus syringae.

geography: Pakistan, especially northern and northwestern Pakistan (Punjab, North-West Frontier Province, Baluchistan, Northern areas, and Azad Kashmir), including Gilgit-Baltistan, Salt Range, Galliyat, Deserts, Sindh, Baluchistan, AJK and Northern Himalayan areas
notes: Updated April 2017 (Contact information, staff, URL, important collectors, geography updated). The herbarium contains specimens of 150 families of flowering plants along with collections of gymnosperms (conifers) and lower plants (non-seed producing plants) and all of these plant species are entirely indigenous in nature. The collection is currently being digitized, and the herbarium staff building an electronic Herbarium Catalogue containing images of the specimens and information taken from their collection labels.  The overall objective of digitization of the herbarium is to link this national wealth of the country with international research institutes and global web of knowledge.  The oldest specimens were collected some 50 years ago and 52 per cent of all flowering plant genera are represented in the collection.   The herbarium scientists are committed to making this important collection more accessible to botanists and others, wherever they may be, for use in their own projects: particularly in biodiversity, conservation and sustainable development. Currently ongoing projects linked to herbarium include taxonomic studies of wild vegetables, wild edible fruits, biodiesel plants based resources, medicinal plants and pollen flora of Northern Pakistan.
associatedHerbaria: QAU Botanical Garden, department of plant sciences.

Specimens are part of the John Muir National Historic Site museum collection where they are stored and maintained according to National Park Service museum standards. . In an effort to gain better intellectual and physical control over the specimens, we are beginning a partnership project with the University and Jepson Herbaria at the University of California, Berkeley, to have students and staff mount, digitize and catalog the Muir plant specimens. As a result of this project, the catalog records will be made available for viewing by the public on-line via the CollectionSpace program on the University and Jepson Herbaria website. Specimen images and catalog data will be available by UC/JEPS on public portal: https://ucjeps.cspace.berkeley.edu/ucjeps_project/public/publicsearch/. Research requests are by appointment only

geography: Kamchatsky Kray (Kamchatka peninsula with adjacent regions and islands)
notes: Entered Jul 2016. The herbarium was established in 1987 with the foundation of the laboratory for plant resources of the Kamchatka Division of the Pacific Geographical Institute, FEB RAS (today, this laboratory is called: Laboratory for Plant Ecology of the Kamchatka Branch of the Pacific Geographical Institute). The herbarium contains collections of vascular plants, mosses, lichens, and fungi that have been compiled by members of the Kamchatka Division PGI FEB RAS as well as by scientists from associated organizations during floristic and geobotanical field studies on the Kamchatka peninsula and its adjacent regions and islands. As of today, 6100 specimens have been catalogued. The remaining 1640 specimens are the reference collection for the “Flora of the Russian Far East (Flora Exsicata) by Charkevich and Buch (1999). Digitizing and cataloging of the Flora Exsicata specimens is in progress.  Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences.

name: NA
exchange: Vascular plants of Europe, especially Poland and tropical Africa
notes: Updated Jul 2017 (geocoordinates updated). 30 000 bryophytes and lichens of KRA on permanent loan to KRAM. Private herbarium of Jan Kornas and Anna Medwecka-Kornas (40 000 specimens) stored at KRA. There are preserved also two historical herbaria of 18th century. The first is a book of 27 sheets (24,5 x 40 cm) with 172 specimens of plants labelled with pre-Linnean latin names. It was made by an unknown author after 1700. The second herbarium consists of four unified folio volumes (32 x 44,5 cm). The volume 1 includes 104 sheets, vol. 2 - 98, vol. 3 - 100, vol. 4 - 104 sheets and the herbarium contains 383 species of plants. After the title page the owner of the herbarium was ANDRZEJ BADURSKI (1740-1789), lecturer of medicine at Cracow University, educated at the University of Bologna. The herbarium was probably made under the supervision of GAETANO LORENZO MONTI (1712-1797), professor of medical botany at Bologna University. The Paleobotanical collection, of the Paleobotanic Museum , has a rich collection of over 150 thousand specimens of fossil plants (including microscopic preparations of the anatomy of certain plants) from all geological periods of Earth's history, from the Devonian period of the Holocene. The oldest exhibits date from the late XIX century (M. RACIBORSKI). One of the most valuable is a collection of Devonian first land plants. In the collection, there are several types of plants from the Devonian and Carboniferous period

name: NA
notes: Updated Oct 2017.  Herbarium of the Botany Department of the Saint Petersburg State University (LECB) is one of the largest University Herbarium of Russia. Its funds contain at least 800,000 herbarium sheets of higher plants. Now Herbarium collection is unique in the structure of the University, both in historical and in scientific terms by geographical coverage and systematic collection of funds, the existing type specimens (more than 3,500 types in the present, as we found). The type collection includes quite a significant amount of rare and original authentic specimens collected by various botanists such as E. Boissier (1810–1885), V. Borbas (1844–1905), H. Cuming (1791–1865), A.P. Decandolle (1778–1841), J. Forster (1754–1794), W. Hooker (1785–1865), G. Schimper (1804–1878), V. Tineo (1791–1856), W. Besser (1784–1842), ?. Bunge (1803–1890), R. Hohenacker (1798–1872), G. Karelin (1801–1872), I. Kirilov(1822–1842), St. Krasheninnikov (1711–1755), C. Ledebour (1785–1851), R. Maack (1825–1886), K. Meinshausen (1819–1899), C. Meyer (1795–1855), ?. Nordmann (1803–1866), P. Pallas (1741–1811), Ch. Steven (1781–1863), N. Turzaninov (1793–1863), ?. Shrenk (1816–1876) etc.   This Herbarium is probably one of the oldest as Russia storage facilities. The oldest herbarium specimens kept in LECB, belong to the middle of XVII century, or even the end of XVI century. Prelinnean specimens found by us in G. Bongard (1786–1839) and E. Lindemann (1825–1901) collections. Thus, according to Lindemann, in his collection during his lifetime were kept for more than 60 specimens collected by prelinnean F. Ambrosi (2 sheets), J. Breyn (1637–1697) (36), C. Bauhin (1) (1560–1624), A. Clegero (1) (he collected Juniperus japonica from Japan in 1688), J. Gerard (1545–1612) (1), J. Gmelin (1709–1755) (20). Many specimens found in Bongard’s herbarium, but how many relics it contains is difficult to say, since Bongard did not kept accounting herbarium revenues. Currently LECB, revealed more than 60 prelinnean specimens. The most of them were found in herbaria Bongard – specimens belonged to J. Commelin (1629–1692), C. Commelin (1668–1731), Breyn, P. Hermann (1646–1695), G. Steller (1709–1746), Gmelin etc., as well as in the herbarium Lindemann to Bauhin, Clegero, Breyn, Gmelin, etc. Currently, the oldest specimen found in LECB, is a specimen of C. Bauhin (1560–1624) – Jucca gloriosa L., without an exact date on the label, but, undoubtedly, belonged to Bauhin. Some of the old specimens have only historical interest, other are syntypes for species of C. Linnaeus (1707–1778), P. Pallas (1741–1811), J. Lamarck (1744–1829) and others, which is why value these specimens is particularly large. Examples of these types: Melanthium sibiricum L., Anthericum calyculatum L., Convolvolus ammannii Desr., Convolvulus lineatus L., Yucca gloriosa L., Andromeda stelleriana Pall., Claytonia arctica Adam, Claytonia sibirica L., Alyssum hyperboreum L., Phlox sibirica L. Thus, LECB is the third in Russia after Moscow State University Herbarium (MW) and Komarov Botanical Institute RAS (LE), which revealed prelinnean specimens, and some of which refers to syntypes of Linnean taxa.   Private herbaria of H. G. Bongard (25 000 specimens) and E. E. Lindemann (200 000 specimens) housed at LECB.  Two contributors to Bongard’s collection deserve special mention: Johann Jacob Boeber (1746-1820) and Carl Ludwig Willdenow (1765-1812).   It was Boeber’s personal herbarium the first collection to have been acquired in 1823 by the Department of Botany and added to Bongard’s own collection, comprising at the time 6,783 species. According to Bongard, Boeber’s collection of 7,000 specimens, representing 6,000 vascular plants and 1,000 cryptogams, was for the most part “badly pressed, or damaged by use”. Subsequently, and for reasons unknown, most of its specimens had been transferred to the Botanical Museum and are presently kept at the Herbarium of the Komarov Botanical Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences (LE).   That Bongard’s collection at LECB includes some of Willdenow’s original specimens is not a widely known fact, either in Russia, or in the West. Our research indicates that there are 1,089 Willdenow’s specimens at LECB, with 104 of them authenticated by labels in his hand. This alone makes Bongard’s collection at LECB quite unique, both as a historic and scientific record. The only other Willdenow herbarium sheets in Russia, with labels in his hand, are found at LE (limited to algae), and at MW, the Moscow University Herbarium (about 50 sheets).  Our preliminary study of Bongard’s collection at LECB identified around 1,450 type specimens (mostly syntypes and isotypes) that are currently kept in the Herbarium’s type collection of about 3,500 specimens. Among them, 42 type specimens of the Restionaceae, with 33 of them described by K.S. Kunth (1788-1850). Kunth, along with several other taxonomists, studied specimens collected by J.F. Drége (1794-1881) at the Cape of Good Hope and in other districts of the Cape Province in South Africa. There are also Bongard’s own type specimens, such as ??rallorhiza mertensiana Bong., collected by K.H. Mertens at Sitka, Alaska, with labels both in Bongard’s and Mertens’s hand. However, most of the types described by Bongard are kept at LE. The LECB specimens seem to be duplicates of those, with more detailed labels, found at LE.   Literature about Herbarium (LECB) http://www.rasl.ru/e_resours/Gerbary_bin/uchrezhdeniya/spbgu.html

Dr. J. Frenguelli donated the reference collections of Möller and Tempère & Peragallo and his personal library that contains classical diatom literature available to all researchers. Information about the new 421 taxa described by Frenguelli (number of slides available associated to each taxon and presence/absence of unmounted material) are published in:   "Catálogo de los géneros, species y taxa infraespecíficos erigidos por J. Frenguelli/Catalogue of the genera, species and infraspecifica taxa erected by J. Frenguelli". Sar, E. A., Sala S. E., Sunesen, I., Henninger, M. S. & Montastruc M. 2009. Diatom Mongraphs 10. Edited by A. Witkowski. ARG Gantner Verlag, Ruggell, Liechtenstein, 419 pp.   The Herbarium also houses the collections of Dr. Sebastián Guarrera devoted to freshwater microalgae from different areas of Argentina mainly from Patagonia and Pampasic regions, and those of Dr. Martha Ferrario of marine phytoplankton from Antarctic and Southwestern Atlantic Ocean.

An electronic database “A list of vascular plants of Magadan Region” (Chukotka is not included) with Latin and Russian names indicates for each species frequency of occurrence according to 6 floristic regions suggested by A.P. Khokhryakov (1985), literature, synonyms and notes. This list is constantly being corrected and supplemented on the basis of revision of herbarium funds, new findings and depending on the newest works of taxonomists (www.ibpn.ru/en/publications/11-databases/3-data-base-a-list-of-the-vascular-plants-species-of-magadan-region). There are 32 species of vascular plants from Magadan Region (Russia) described by A.P. Khokhryakov deposited in the collection: 20 species represented by isotypes, 10 - isotypes and paratypes, 2 - paratypes. The photo of these herbarium specimens and  herbarium labels one can be found here: http://www.ibpn.ru/kollektsii/261-tipovye-obraztsy-sosudistykh-rastenij.  Fungi: over 10000 specimens of 700 species of Agaricales and Aphyllophorales, main collection from Magadan, Chukotka, and a small collection from Russian south Far East and European part (Kostroma and Leningrad Regions).  Lichens: 4300 specimens of 270 species from Magadan Region.  Bryophytes: approximately. 4000 specimens of 290 species (common species from Magadan, Chukotka, Taymir).  Seed collection: 2600 samples of 1400 species of vascular plants from Magadan Region, Russian South Far East, Ural and Siberia.

notes: Entered Aug 2017. The Herbarium MAR has a recent foundation date, July 2013, but it has a collection of plants that have been collected since 1980 in the State of Maranhão. Although recently, the collection is increasing due to developing undergraduate and postgraduate studies. It has records of plants of dune and restinga areas, as well as ecotonal environments that are a particular characteristic of Maranhão State. A collection of the families Sapotaceae, Myrtaceae, Poaceae, Arecaceae, Solanaceae, Asteraceae, Rubiaceae, Convolvulaceae and Cactaceae; And a collection of the areas belonging to the Maranhão Amazon is beginning to expand the records of the species of the Northeast of Brazil.

name: NA
notes: Entered Jul 2013. The ontogenetic herbarium is herbarium of plants of different stages of individual development. Ontogenetic states were revealed with the use of the concept of discrete description of ontogenesis taking into account morphological features-markers (table). The goal is to document every species in the Ontogenetic Herbariumwith specimens in different ontogenetic states from plantules to the senile plants (complete ontogenesis). Our Ontogenetic herbarium has duplicates of some species that we are ready to interchange, and we can also take herbarium of ontogenesis of any types of plants on storage. Exhibits in herbarium are arranged in alphabetical order of latin names of families and species inside these families. Systematic catalogue renovates constantly, the ontogenetic states of species, places of collections and main collectors are indicated in it. The Ontogenetic herbarium in an accessible form for use, and includes 5330 mounted sheets of 607 species of plants from 369 genera and 86 families, and also 1 lichen and 2 types of gymnospermous and higher cryptogams plants. It is used both in scientific and pedagogical aims. The Ontogenetic Herbarium allows users to get skills of determination of ontogenetic states of plants of different biomorphes and to apply them for study and maintenance of population biodiversity. Today the Ontogenetic Herbarium is included in the department "Population-Ontogenetic Museum."

name: NA
geography: Southern France; Mediterranean region; Réunion Island.
notes: updated Jul 2012.   Loans: Types not sent on loan.  History and specificity:  Initiated at the beginning of the 19th century, now with about 250 000 samples, this collection reflects: 1) the history of Marseille: port open to the world, especially to the former French overseas territories and 2) the competence and influence of the 19th century Provençal naturalists. Today this herbarium includes: currently active herbaria, historical collections of the 19th and the 20th century of the South-East of the France and various herbaria relating to France's colonial history.  Currently active herbaria: 1) a general world herbarium of vascular plants initiated by Louis Castagne in 1820, 2) a general herbarium of vascular plants of France, 3) a general herbarium of vascular plants of the French Mediterranean area, 4) a cytogenetic herbarium of plants mainly collected and studied by J. Contandriopoulos and R. Verlaque, 5) a general world herbarium of lichen and 6) a general world herbarium of bryophyte. Historical and prestigious collections of the 19th and the 20th century of the South-East of the France, corresponding to the first "modern" flora : 1) Herbier Louis Castagne (Catalogue des plantes qui croissent naturellement dans le département des Bouches-du-Rhône), 2) Honoré Ardoino (Flore analytique du département des Alpes-maritimes), 3) Honoré Roux (Catalogue des plantes de Provence spontanées ou généralement cultivées)… Various herbaria relating to France's colonial history : 1) Herbier Père Antoine Duss des Antilles (Flore phanérogamique des Antilles françaises, Guadeloupe et Martinique), 2) Herbier Henri Jumelle and Henri Perrier de la Bathie for Madagascar (numerous publications among the Catalogue des plantes de Madagascar), 3) Herbier Eugène Jacob de Cordemoy for La Réunion (Flore de l'Ile de la Réunion), used for the " Flore des Mascareignes ", 4) Herbier Georg. Zenker (Cameroun), Herbier Boery (Mauritanie) for the " Afrique Orientale Française ", 5) Herbier Pennel and Metzger for the Nouvelle Calédonie.  Moreover, the botanical collections of the University include the Musée Colonial de Marseille founded in 1893 as a part of the Institut Colonial de Marseille. This collection contains plant samples from overseas selected and used for food (fruits, vegetables, cereals, oils, etc.), as condiments and spices, for pharmaceuticals and for industry (rubber, wood, fibres, etc.).

The authentic specimens of the books 'Eriocaulaceae in India' (R. Ansari), 'Nymphaeceae in India' (R. Ansari), 'Ferns and Fern allies of Kerala' (P.V. Madhusoodanan) etc. are deposited in this herbarium. Type specimens of few new species published by scientists in this institute and from other institutions in Kerala are also deposited. This is the only herbarium in south India where specimens of lower groups of plants are preserved.

name: NA
notes: Updated July 2017 (general update). Mercer’s herbarium specimen data and living. collections are linked and managed using current BG-BASE software. Mercer’s vouchered herbarium specimens and/or living collections will support the Plant Collections Network, formerly, the North American Plant Collections Consortium of the American Public Gardens Association and currently support Botanic Gardens Conservation International (BGCI) database. In April 2014, the herbarium joined Mercer’s reference library, archives, laboratories and seed bank within Mercer’s newly-renovated research facility (~ 3,100 sf), the Mercer Botanical Center (MBC). The MBC provides additional dedicated space to accommodate expansion of the herbarium collections. In October 2016, the SBSC herbarium, botanical library and illustration collections were transferred to the Mercer Botanic Gardens as a long-term loan. Physical transfer of the SBSC collections was completed spring 2017 and the collections are available to researchers. Digitization of the SBSC collections is underway. Mercer Botanic Gardens provides citizen scientist training programs including the Texas Gulf Coast Gardener, Texas Master Gardener and Texas Master Naturalist, Texas Invaders and RBG Kew Millennium Seed Bank Training programs. The MERCA and SBSC herbarium collections support these education programs and facilitate training of herbarium volunteers. Mercer Botanic Gardens is a participating institution of The Center for Plant Conservation (headquartered at San Diego Zoo Global); is an affiliate of Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center; and is a member of the American Public Gardens Association and Botanic Gardens Conservation International.

notes: Entered 2018. We are a non-governmental organization with research, diffusion, ambiental education and conservation proposal. We have recently created our fungarium to continuing doing research, and to publicate our studies on journals and in a free access web page, to contribute to Chilean fungal knowledge. Then, we will send collections replicates to National Natural History Museum (SGO). We have above of 900 fungal collections, that they are been being incorporated into the collection continuously. Every year we are visiting native Chilean forests to collect fungi, and then do taxonomic and ecological studies.

department: Iran's National Museum of Natural History
notes: The Herbarium of Iran's National Museum of Natural History was first formed in the 1970’s with the proposal of Professor Karl Heinz Rechinger, famous Austrian botanist . This Herbarium has been created in the Department of Environment of Iran with the aim of gathering and maintaining the plant diversity of areas managed by the Department of Environment of Iran and specific habitats. It is to be hoped that in the near future, we will see the development and promotion of this valuable collection by increasing the space and facilities provided, including cabinet rails and assistance of other botanist researchers at the national level.
