collection.string: MO_Missouri Botanical Garden: Missouri Botanical Garden
institutioncode.gbif: Missouri Botanical Garden: Missouri Botanical Garden
name: Missouri Botanical Garden
citation: Magill B, Solomon J, Stimmel H (2019). Tropicos Specimen Data. Missouri Botanical Garden. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/hja69f accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
geography: Worldwide; Central America (especially Costa Rica, Nicaragua, and Panama), tropical South America (especially Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Paraguay, Peru, and Venezuela), Africa, and Madagascar; North America, Neotropics
exchange: Vascular plants and mosses worldwide, especially Central America and South America, Africa, and Madagascar
notes: Algae transferred to UC. Fungi transferred to BPI. Lichens transferred to US. Specimens from Traub Herbarium, transferred to MO in 1984, should be cited as TRA. MO library contains more than 200 000 volumes, about 800 current botanical periodicals and approximately 250 000 items in the archives, including letters, manuscripts, paintings, drawings, photographs, and maps. MO maintains a computerized database, TROPICOS, containing information on names and nomenclature, specimens and literature references for vascular plants and mosses worldwide, including images, synonymy, acceptance and authority files at http://www.tropicos.org. Records since 1975 from <Index to Plant Chromosome Numbers>, now published by MO, are part of database. Flora projects include: <Flora of China>, <Flora de Nicaragua> in conjunction with HNMN, <Flora of Peru> in conjunction with F, <Flora Mesoamericana> in conjunction with BM and MEXU, <Flora of the Venezuelan Guayana>, <Flora of North America>, <Catalog of the Flowering Plants and Gymnosperms of Peru>, and <Catalog of the Vascular Plants of Ecuador> and <Catálogo de las plantas vasculares de Bolivia>  Address for visitors to the Garden (and deliveries that require a street address: 4344 Shaw Blvd., St. Louis, MO 63110).
incorporated herbaria: TRA (3000 specimens) in 1984;mosses of CM in 1981;bryophytes of DEK;bryophytes of SMS;bryophytes of PAC;<Carex> (9700) and bryophytes (702) of WARM in 1998;C. F. Reed Herbarium (160 000 vascular plants; 35 000 bryophytes) in 2001;bryophytes of LAF (30 000 specimens) in 2002;post-1970 bryophyte collections of BUF on loan in 2002;UMO (235,000) in 2015
associatedHerbaria: Missouri Botanical Garden. Shaw Nature Reserve, P.O. Box 38, Gray Summit, Missouri 63039. Washington University. Saint Louis University. University of Missouri-St. Louis. Southern Illinois University, Edwardsville.
physical street address: 4344 Shaw Boulevard, Saint Louis, Missouri 63110, U.S.A.

name: NA
geography: North central and eastern plains of Montana
notes: Entered Feb 2016. The Montana State University Northern Herbarium represents a new repository for plants growing in the diverse habitats associated with this geographical area. In addition to grass- and shrub lands, we house specimen vouchers from localized mountain areas that rise above the plains (e.g., Sweetgrass Hills, Bears Paw and Little Belt Mountains). Plants collected from prairie potholes and limestone outcrops, as well as those from cottonwood dominated riparian areas and gumbo bluffs associated with the Missouri River Breaks, are included in the collection. Voucher age ranges from the early 1900’s to the present and some of these represent plants collected from more well-known regions, e.g., Yellowstone, Rocky Mountain, and Glacier National Parks.

notes: Entered Nov 2016. MUH is currently set up under the aegis of Deptt. of Botany, Mirpur University of Science & Technology (MUST) at Bhimber Campus, District Bhimber (AK) Pakistan. Botanical Library is available to researchers, students, amateur botanists and horticulturists. Albeit library is at infantile stage yet is it has enough national and international books, articles, journals and monograph reprints. MUH has 3000 Seed Germ (SG) plasm (36 families) collection of wild plants of Shiwalik Mountainous Range of Azad Kashmir and Pakistan. MUH has plenty of photographs, botanical art and artifacts on vegetation of the area depicting its conservation status. Currently herbaria specimens has reached ca. 12000 and it is increasing day by day due to continuous efforts of researchers and collectors.

notes: Entered Sep 2009. Specimens are stored in acid free herbarium paper and are kept in metal storage cabinets, while corresponding samples of selected taxa are conserved in 96% ethanol / glycerol (50:50) and/or silicagel dried. The herbarium is equipped with cabinet drier. The herbarium data is completely digitalized (database in FileMaker Pro 9), all herbarium sheets are photographed while (for the moment) web browsing is available for about half of the specimens. Internet access to all the data will be possible by the end of 2009.

name: NA
notes: Entered Jan 2014.The herbarium consists old algae collection (Sandri G. B., Selebam de Cattani M., group of authors – Hel Z., Piasevoli S., Iric A., Župic D. & Župic J.) from Adriatic sea and vascular specimens (collection Studniczka, Andric, Bucic, Cvitanic) from Croatia or Europe. In Carl Studniczka’s herbarium the majority of the herbal plants was collected in Europe (Croatia, Austria, Italy, Montenegro, France, Poland, Czech Republic). Most of the samples of herbarium plants were collected by Studniczka himself. Besides Studniczka, over then 240 collectors or botanists also have been registered. The oldest herbarium sheet dates from 1836, where as the newest ones date from 1904. The vast majority of herbarium sheets was collected during the period from 1871 to 1880.

geography: Philippines, especially the Cordillera Administrative Region
exchange: Some Plants of the Cordillera Administrative Region (CAR), Luzon, Philippines
notes: Updated April 2017 (general update).   Wanted: Other Plants of the Cordillera Administrative Region (CAR), Luzon, Philippines Available: Some Plants of the Cordillera Administrative Region (CAR), Luzon, Philippines  The UP Baguio herbarium started as a student herbarium. It used to be very small with few collections from students and faculty researchers. At present, the herbarium has grown and is focused on keeping representative collections of the flora of the Cordillera Administrative Region, Luzon, Philippines. It is presently the only herbarium in the Region hence many students and researchers use the facility for the identification and verification of their plants for their studies.  The herbarium is active in the collection of plants from various parts of the Cordillera.   The herbarium will be transferred to a new building, the Biodiversity Center of the Cordillera, in the future when the building will have been constructed. There is also a plan for establishing a database of all the collections which will be shared on line. The main constraint of the herbarium is funding to develop and improve it further. There is no library yet and the meager books are the personal collections of the person in charge.  The herbarium is open for donations of taxonomic books and other related literature and materials.

geography: Worldwide, with emphasis on Australia, especially New South Wales
exchange: Australian plants, mainly from New South Wales
notes: NSW fungi have been transferred to the New South Wales Plant Pathology Herbarium (DAR); The Plant Disease Diagnostic Unit contains microfungal and plant pathology collections.  In June 2018, the NSW Government  announced a $60 million investment for a new facility, the Centre of Innovation in Plant Sciences. This project will see a purpose-built, state-of-the-art facility created to protect our nationally and internationally significant collection, recently valued at $280 million. The new facility is to be based in Western Sydney at the Australian Botanic Garden Mount Annan.   The preparation and relocation of the collections to the new facility will have a substantial impact on the operations of NSW until the end of 2021. Beginning April 2019 digitization of the botanical collections will commence, resulting in the generation of 1.4 million specimen images and metadata which will be made available online during the closure of the Herbarium.   Please note the following dates: Access to the NSW collections, including the actioning of loan requests and visitors, will be restricted beginning January 2019. Visitors will not be able to be accommodated from January, 2019. Requests for loans, images, and destructive sampling after January 2019 will not be actioned and we recommend you resubmit your request early in 2022.
incorporated herbaria: Museum of Applied Arts and Sciences, Sydney;NSWF wood (2010);UNSW Australian mosses

The new facility is to be based in Western Sydney at the Australian Botanic Garden Mount Annan.   The preparation and relocation of the collections to the new facility will have a substantial impact on the operations of NSW until the end of 2021. Beginning April 2019 digitization of the botanical collections will commence, resulting in the generation of 1.4 million specimen images and metadata which will be made available online during the closure of the Herbarium.   Please note the following dates: Access to the NSW collections, including the actioning of loan requests and visitors, will be restricted beginning January 2019. Visitors will not be able to be accommodated from January, 2019. Requests for loans, images, and destructive sampling after January 2019 will not be actioned and we recommend you resubmit your request early in 2022.

geography: Worldwide with greatest strength in tropical America and North America
exchange: All groups; mostly tropical America and western U.S.
notes: NY diatoms transferred to CAS in 2002. The Brooklyn Botanic Garden Herbarium (BKL, ca. 350,000 specimens) is maintained separately, but is available for consultation and loans. Botanical library available to all researchers. Library includes over 260 400 volumes (105 000 book and monograph titles and nearly 11 000 serial titles), 125 000 reprints, collections of archives and manuscripts, seed catalogs and index semina, photographs, botanical art, and artifacts. The Library on-line catalog, is accessible at: http://library.nybg.org. Services include interlibrary loan, photocopying, photography, CD-ROM database searches, and literature searches. Most services are for a fee. The Library is the repository for the Taxonomic Literature II (Stafleu and Cowan) data files and for the archives of the American Society of Plant Taxonomists, Council on Botanical and Horticultural Libraries, Mycological Society of America, Organization for Flora Neotropica, Society for Economic Botany, Torrey Botanical Society, and others.

name: NA
notes: Entered Mar 2016. The Oman Botanic Garden, a unique project not only within Oman but the entire Arabian Peninsula, is currently under construction. It aims to present and showcase the native flora and habitats of the country to visitors and offers student, researchers and other botanic gardens (national and international) modern facilities and expertise in a state of the art research centre. The OBG herbarium will be a major focus of the research centre. The herbarium is currently working closely with researchers from within Oman (e.g. Sultan Qaboos University) and international research institutions (e.g. Royal Botanic Gardens of Edinburgh).   Oman’s native flora consists of approximately 1408 species, distributed within highly diverse habitats throughout the country. Remote and inaccessible areas of the country have yet to be studied. There is a relatively high possibility that new plant records will be discovered during the course of OBG’s field collecting trips.   Although we are at the beginning of a large task, the OBG herbarium collection is constantly growing and aims at increasing our specimen numbers vastly within the next two to three years. On our many field trips throughout Oman, collecting herbarium vouchers is of critical importance. Of nearly all the species collected so far, multiple vouchers are available. The wide range of morphological variation within and between Oman’s diverse habitats is captured for many of the species. Vouchers of rare and endemic species are included in our collection as well.  In Oman, we are so far the only herbarium/institution that regularly undertakes scientific curation and physical curation inspections by trained staff and documents all procedures

geography: Worldwide, especially British Isles, arctic, and South America.
notes: Updated Jan 2014. The Fielding Herbarium contains all non-British material collected by former Department of Botany staff since 1769, and since it was largely obtained through purchase of material at auctions in the early 19th century, it is particularly rich in type material. The Druce Herbarium contains all British phanerogams that were collected later than 1769. The history of OXF has been comprehensively studied by H. M. Clokie (1964; An account of the herbaria of the Department of Botany in the University of Oxford," Oxford University Press).
associatedHerbaria: <Associated garden:> Oxford Botanic Garden, High Street.

organization: Hugh Nicholson and Tony Abbott Herbarium
notes: Updated Mar 2017 (contact updated). The Hugh Nicholson and Tony Abbott Herbarium is a collection of flora mainly of the Pondoland Centre of Endemism (PCE), which forms part of the Maputaland-Pondoland-Albany region of endemism, one of only 34 internationally recognised areas of conservation significance. The PCE herbarium is housed in the Umtamvuna Nature Reserve, a formally protected area managed by the provincial nature conservation agency, Ezemvelo KwaZulu-Natal Wildlife, and is staffed by local volunteers. For continuity, the first point of contact is the Ezemvelo KwaZulu-Natal Wildlife District Ecologist for the central and southeastern region of the province. From there correspondence will be directed to the relevant person(s) to deal with queries.

name: NA
section: Petersburg Garden Club Lee Park Herbarium
notes: Updated Feb 2016. The Lee Park Herbarium was begun in 1937 as part of a WPA project to create a wildflower sanctuary. In addition to clearing land and planting native plants, the WPA workers were taught to collect and preserve specimens. This part of the collection comprises 325 specimens; collection ended about 1940. In the 1990s, Donna M.E. Ware, botanist at the College of William and Mary, began collecting in Lee Park anew. Her goal was to determine if the original 325 species still grew there, and then expanded her project to collect other plants in the Park and watershed. The Ware portion of the herbariam comprises 800 specimens and collection continues on this portion.  The herbarium collection includes 238 corresponding watercolors exquisitely painted by Bessie Neimeyer Marshall during the depression era in the 1930’s. The botanical renderings are showcased in With Paintbrush and Shovel: Preserving Virginia’s Wildflowers.
associatedHerbaria: Lewis Ginter Botanical Garden, 1800 Lakeside Ave. Rich VA 23228

notes: Updated Mar 2017 (general update).  Average accession rates are about 1,000 specimens per year. PPI exchanges duplicates with some academic institutions around the world and focuses on acquiring plants from East Asia (especially mainland China and Japan). In addition to various domestic universities and botanical research institutions, current targets for such exchanges also encompass major universities, herbaria, museums and botanical gardens in Asian countries. PPI has Southern Taiwan vascular plants available for exchange. PPI specimens are made with the utmost care, and each specimen label contains a complete set of information. PPI preserves 21 new species, 2 new record family, 21 new record genus, 73 new record species, 4 new combination, 31 corrections. Especially, there are 23 Holotypes preserved in PPI.

name: NA
organization: Royal College of Physicians of London
notes: Entered Nov 2018. Most of PSGB herbarium transferred via K in 2014. The herbarium was founded initially as PSGB in 1872. It is planned to make a database of the plants and photos available on the web in 2019-2020.  We may enter the information using the BRAHMS database program or keep it in an Excel spreadsheet.  Founded and used by Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain [Herbarium code PSGB] to teach Materia Medica to pharmacy students from 1872 to 1968. Then given to University of Bradford [Code BRAD] for a similar purpose until transferred to Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew [Code K] in 1995 and then to Royal College of Physicians of London in 2014.  Used now to illustrate history of plants in medicine and for other uses. Particularly strong on plants of medical and economic importance collected in former British colonies in India and nearby areas of Far East, SE Asia and Africa, as well as other specimens illustrating economically important plants mainly from Britain, Europe and South and Central America. Many entries include name in local dialect and information about local uses.
associatedHerbaria: Garden of Medicinal Plants of Royal College of Physicians of London

name: NA
geography: Rocky Mountain Western Slope, Gunnison Basin, Colorado
notes: Updated Feb 2017. (general update). The herbarium was established shortly after the founding of the Rocky Mountain Biological Laboratory (RMBL), in 1929 by Harriet G. Barclay from the University of Tulsa (TULS). It has served as a resource for plant identification and distribution information for students and researchers at the lab and contains vouchers from many research projects over the past 80 years. The collection is completely databased, imaged, and searchable online at: http://intermountainbiota.org. The laboratory/field station, located at over 9500 ft.in the Elk Mountains of Western Colorado, is open and accessible seasonally from May-October. The collection is curated by volunteers from other institutions who work at the lab each summer (currently C.F. Rick Williams, Curator, Ray J. Davis Herbarium [IDS], Idaho Museum of Natural History).

organization: Department of Agricultural and Forest Sciences
section: Herbarium of Agricultural and Forest Sciences
notes: Entered Jan 2014.As a result of University reform introduced by the Italian Government, faculties were transformed into mega-Departments. The Department of Agriculture and Forestry was thus established in January 2013 as a substitute for the Agricultural Faculty. The Department includes botanists (teaching systematics, physiology, forestry botany, geobotany), agronomist and other professors teaching silviculture whose research activities in the field provides for the collection and identification of numerous herbarium specimens. Besides in the subject “Forest Botany and Mycology” all students are required to submit for the final exam an herbarium of dried plants and fungi collected during the lessons in the field including at least 25 species.  The new herbarium currently includes ca. 5000 specimens (plants, shrubs, fungi) but this number is expected to increase rapidly.

notes: Updated July 2017 (general update).  SBSC is a facility of Spring Branch Independent School District. In October 2016, the SBSC herbarium, botanical library and illustration collections were transferred to the Mercer Botanic Gardens as a long-term loan. Physical transfer of the SBSC collections was completed spring 2017 and the collections are available to researchers. Digitization of the SBSC collections is underway. Mercer Botanic Gardens provides citizen scientist training programs including the Texas Gulf Coast Gardener, Texas Master Gardener and Texas Master Naturalist, Texas Invaders and RBG Kew Millennium Seed Bank Training programs. The MERCA and SBSC herbarium collections support these education programs and facilitate training of herbarium volunteers. Mercer Botanic Gardens is a participating institution of The Center for Plant Conservation (headquartered at San Diego Zoo Global); is an affiliate of Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center; and is a member of the American Public Gardens Association and Botanic Gardens Conservation International.

name: NA
organization: University of California-Berkeley, Sagehen Creek Field Station
notes: Entered Dec 2011. Sagehen Creek Field Station is approximately 8000 acres, and encompasses a diverse cross section of the Sierra Nevada from the Pacific Crest (el. 8000 ft) to the eastern slope (el. 6400 ft). Habitats include yellow pine, mixed conifer, and red fir forests, as well as brushfields, scattered mountain meadows, and fens.  The Sagehen Herbarium is comprised of two related collections: "Herbarium of the Sagehen Creek Field Station" and "Flora of California." The Sagehen Creek collection is fairly comprehensive of plants found on the reserve. The "Flora of California" collection draws from a broader area, but is still focused on Sierra Nevada specimens.

We are pleased to inform you that custom problems were solved by our Institution and therefore we can receive loans, safe and secure, at our traditional address. Finally, the shipment/s of botanical specimens should be sent by regular mail, i.e. not by private couriers (such as FedEx, DHL and so on).  SI contains more than 700,000 specimens, including 6000 types, 2400 periodicals, 8500 books, and the updated checklist of vascular plants can be viewed on the SI web page. SI is part of Academia Nacional de Ciencias Exactas, Físicas y Naturales de Buenos Aires and Consejo Nacional de Investigaciones Científicas y Técnicas (CONICET).

notes: Entered Dec 2017. The Herbarium SLUI has a collection of plants that have been collected since 1988 in the State of Maranhão. Since 2009, the Herbarium has been registered in the Brazilian Herbarium Network of the Brazilian Botanic Society (SBB) as Herbarium Rosa Mochel (SLUI), and in 2010 it joined the INCT - Virtual Herbarium Institute of Flora and Fungi of Brazil. With the support of INCT - Virtual Herbarium of Flora and Fungi of Brazil and FAPEMA, SLUI began the process of computerizing the data of the collection, and its inclusion in the speciesLink network, of the Reference Center on Environmental Information. In 2017 the scanning of the collection with image capture began. Currently 131 exsicatas (about 2% of the collection) are available online on the speciesLink network. The SLUI collection has about 5,500 samples of botanical material, mainly exsicates, predominating the angiosperms, with 117 families represented. The collection also has 50 pteridophytes, 26 bryophytes, 24 macroscopic algae and two gymnosperms. In addition to the collection of exsicatas, a xiloteca (174 specimens), a carpoteca (50 specimens), a collection of seeds (35 samples) and a small collection of macroscopic fungi (10 samples) are available. The collections represent mainly the vegetation of the state: Amazonian forest; Thick; The majority of samples come from the State of Maranhão (70%), although there is a collection of flora from 15 states in Brazil, mainly from donations. The main families represented are Fabaceae (616 records), Malvaceae (420), Cyperaceae (340), Malpighiaceae (290) and Asteraceae (270).

notes: Updated April 2017 (address, contact information, notes updated). Most of STEU transferred to NBG.  The Stellenbosch University Herbarium has been downscaled, now only to include historical collections of southern African Pelargonium and Zygophyllum. These collections include many type specimens. In addition there is a regional (Stellenbosch area) collection which is maintained but not expanded. For the rest, the herbarium is dedicated to the research collections of current staff of Department of Botany and Zoology at Stellenbosch University.  There is no curator. Prof. L Dreyer overseas the academic management of the herbarium, and Me. Law-Brown takes care of physical curation of the regional and specialist collections. Each academic staff member curates and maintains their own research collections.

notes: St. Mary’s University is a small liberal arts and science institution with a developing science program. This is a teaching and research herbarium based on 50 years of collections by I. D. Macdonald. The herbarium also is the official repository for collections from the adjacent Fish Creek Provincial Park. As well, the collection houses many vouching specimens for Dr. McLean’s research into Thesium ramosum Hayne (Thesiaceae), and Macdonald’s research on the vascular plant floras of 1) the LaCloche Mountains (Ontario); 2) the City of Terre Haute (Indiana); 3) the Rattray’s Marsh Conservation Area (Ontario).    The herbarium collection currently represents157 Families, 742 Genera and 1483 Species.   The current accessioned collections are from the following jurisdictions: Ontario (915 specimens), Alberta (908), Indiana (389), Saskatchewan (353), British Columbia (332), Montana (156), Manitoba (156), and the remainder are from across the continent.   As well, there are well over 1,000 additional collections representing an additional over 200 species waiting for processing and official accessioning into the herbarium.

The number of specimens in the herbarium is 918, comprising 556 species of vascular plants, seven algae and five bryophytes. The original total certainly included two further species of vascular plant, each represented by a single specimen.

name: NA
notes: Updated Nov 2017. The herbarium was presented to Stonyhurst College in 1898 by James Ward’s son, also James (educated at Stonyhurst from 1860 onwards). The notes relating to the gift state that James Ward began collecting for his British herbarium in 1825, and by 1871 had amassed 1,753 specimens. There is a second herbarium described as ‘Exotic’ which features specimens from Ireland and Switzerland, these last were collected in 1864. The Exotic Herbarium is described as being of the same size as the British. They are described using the Linnaean system. The collection is housed separately from the other Scientific collections, and is in the same folders and order as when it was donated in c1898. It has, to the best of my knowledge, never been examined by specialists and there is no catalogue or database of the Herbarium.

notes: The main activities at TAN Herbarium are the following - Conservation of herbarium 350 000 mounted specimens divided into 280 families, 1 885 genera and 8 745 species (2019) - Inventory and collection of herbarium specimens - Receipt of collected botanical samples from plant collectors - Mandated by the Malagasy Government to receive the duplicate of specimens collected by foreign and national researchers before any specimens exportation. - Digitizing and data-basing by using Botanical Research And Herbarium Management System (BRAHMS) software. - Support tools for foreign and national researchers and high school students.  - Assessment, review of conservation status of malagasy plants. - Partnership with national institutions (Herbier TEF, DBEV and ENS) and international organizations (MBG, RBG Kew, CAS, HBV and IRD). - Supervision of trainee students from public and private universities (on average 60 per year).

notes: The main activities at TAN Herbarium are the following - Conservation of herbarium 350 000 mounted specimens divided into 280 families, 1 885 genera and 8 745 species (2019) - Inventory and collection of herbarium specimens - Receipt of collected botanical samples from plant collectors - Mandated by the Malagasy Government to receive the duplicate of specimens collected by foreign and national researchers before any specimens exportation. - Digitizing and data-basing by using Botanical Research And Herbarium Management System (BRAHMS) software. - Support tools for foreign and national researchers and high school students.  - Assessment, review of conservation status of malagasy plants. - Partnership with national institutions (Herbier TEF, DBEV and ENS) and international organizations (MBG, RBG Kew, CAS, HBV and IRD). - Supervision of trainee students from public and private universities (on average 60 per year).

section: Billie L. Turner Plant Resources Center
geography: Texas; southwestern U.S.; Latin America, especially Mexico and northern Central America; worldwide, with emphasis on Latin America
notes: Updated Aug 2017 (Herbarium name updated). The C. L. Lundell herbarium (LL) integrated at TEX. Specimens from Lundell herbaria (LL and UTD) should be cited as LL. TEX Philippine myxomycetes of C. J. Alexopoulos transferred to LAM. TEX fungi (1116 specimens) transferred to NY in 1990. H.-Dietmar Behnke, who worked at the University of Heidelberg, kept a personal herbarium of vouchers for his extensive work on sieve-element plastids, published from the 1960s through the 1990s. Upon retirement he gave that collection to TEX (where we maintain it is a separate collection). The collection consists of 2399 sieve-plastid vouchers, received in 2000-2001.

notes: The Troy University Herbarium (TROY) was established in 1954 as a teaching herbarium by Dr. Robert Dietz, who served as curator. In 1961, the herbarium was moved from its original location in the basement of Bibb Graves Hall into the new science building, McCall Hall. This 528 ft2 room served both as the herbarium and a paleobotany laboratory. It remained in this location until 1988 when Dietz retired. At that time, the herbarium was closed and all of the specimens were destroyed. In 1997, the TROY Herbarium was reestablished by Dr. Alvin Diamond and Dr. Michael Woods. In 1999, the collection had grown to approximately 3500 mounted specimens and the herbarium was moved to rooms 125 and 127 of the Math Science Complex (MSCX) (formally McCall Hall). The two rooms totaled 443 ft2, which resulted in a 16% reduction in floor space from the previous location. At the end of 2005, with 19 herbarium cabinets and a collection of approximately 19,000 mounted specimens, the herbarium had outgrown its space. The Curators wrote a five-year plan for the herbarium and submitted it to the Troy University Administration. With support of the Department Chair, Dean, Assistant Provost, and Provost, the herbarium was moved during 2006 to its current location, MSCX 216, which consists of 1058 ft2. Since moving to its current location, the collection has grown to over 44,000 specimens with an average annual growth of over 2,000. This makes TROY one of the fastest-growing herbarium in the southeastern United States. Currently, 100 percent of all vascular plant specimens deposited in the TROY Herbarium have been databased and imaged. Additionally, nonvascular plants have been databased.   In 2017, the Dean of the College of Arts and Sciences (CAS) approved an additional 220 square foot room (MSCX 223) immediately across the hallway from the herbarium (MSCX 216). This will allow us to relocate the plant dryer, freezer, mounting table, shelving for storage, filing cabinet for records pertaining to loans and exchanges, two data basing computers and imaging equipment to MSCX 223. This will increase the safety of the collection by keeping all specimens outside of the herbarium until they have been processed and frozen.   All Alabama specimens are available on the Alabama Plant Atlas http://floraofalabama.org/

notes: Updated Dec 2017. The specimens of the phanerogamic herbarium comes mainly from Italy (particularly from the South-Eastern Alps and the classical Karst regions) and the Mediterranean basin. Numerous samples also come from Europe, North America (Canada, United States), Japan, Canary Islands. There are also specimens used for the "descriptio Florae Italiae" of Pignatti (1982) and a rich collection of Genisteae, which was the subject of numerous systematic, chorological and palynological studies. The lichen samples come mostly from Italy and Europe as well as from non-European countries, particularly Asia (mainly from Japan), Alaska-Yukon, Northern Ontario, Svalbard Archipelago, Canary Islands, SW USA, Mexico, Tierra del Fuego and Antartica. The lichenological herbarium is fully computerized and can be consulted at the link: http://dryades.units.it/italic/index.php?procedure=tsb . The Antarctic lichen database can be consulted at the following link: http://dbiodbs.units.it/antartide/victoria . Algae specimens were collected mainly in the Mediterranean Basin (Adriatic Sea, Aegean Sea, Tyrrhenian Sea, Ligurian Sea, coasts around Sicily and Sardinia), but there are also samples coming from the Atlantic (North Sea and English and French coasts), Central-Southern Americas, African-Asian and Australian areas. Algae databases can be found at the link: http://dbiodbs.units.it/carso/chiavi_pub51?org=algae. Dichotomic identification key of the red calcareous algae (Corallinales) of the Mediterranean is also available.

rightsholder: UFACPZ - Herbário da Universidade Federal do Acre
exchange: Vascular plants, fungi, algae of Acre and Rondonia
notes: Entered Jul 2010. The Herbarium of the Universidade Federal do Acre (UFACPZ) was founded in 1979. Much of the collection is the product of a collaborative research program with The New York Botanical Garden (NY). UFACPZ exchanges specimens with major Brazilian herbaria and with herbaria in neighboring Peru and Bolivia. As of 2010 the entire collection is being imaged and data-based using BRAHMS. The data stored in the Herbarium UFACPZ are of priority use for educational, scientific and public management. No aspect of this collection may be used without proper legal permission for any commercial purpose or one that generates income

name: UFG - Herbário da Universidade Federal de Goiás
citation: de Oliveira Diniz D (2019). UFG - Herbário da Universidade Federal de Goiás. Version 1.55. Universidade Federal de Goiás. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/jn3v2g accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
rightsholder: UFG - Herbário da Universidade Federal de Goiás
notes: The Herbarium was established in 1968 and is registered in the Index Herbariorum, in the Netherlands - international headquarters. It is the depository of more than 60 thousand plants, mainly derived from a survey carried out by Flora of the States of Goiás and Tocantins - Rizzo Collection, which currently has 48 volumes published. In addition to attending other units of the UFG itself and several national and international research institutions, it serves as a support for the elaboration of theses and for the community, identifying medicinal, toxic and ornamental plants.

notes: Entered Jun 2016. The collection of algae is related to the Biological Collection of the Universidad Católica Norte at Coquimbo (http://www.redbiodiversidad.cl/ ) which is associated to the Chilean Biodiversity network, related to several universities, to the Minister of the Environment and to the National Natural History Museum (SGO). The collection includes about 1150 specimens. This is material in sheet form, algae fundamentally from the Chilean coast, Mediterranean coast, the US and the Caribbean. The information is computerized and continues to grow. The Herbarium is deposited at the Faculty of Marine Sciences. The collection is part of the Marine Botany Laboratory, and it constitutes an element of support for research and teaching in the university. This service is intended to provide scientific and technical support for research groups, public institutions and private companies.

notes: The UNG Gainesville Herbarium was formally established in 2018 by a University of North Georgia Presidential Innovation Award, an internal grant which funded our ability to archive and document plant species in north Georgia, USA. The collection is being developed from several decades of legacy specimens which had not been adequately mounted, labeled, or documented, as well as research specimens collected since 2014. name: NA
notes: Types: Buellia insularicola (Holotype), Lecanora kohu (Holotype), Cladia blanchonii (Isotype)  Scope: The Flora and Lichenized Mycobiota of New Zealand. UNITEC has an emphasis on the northern part of New Zealand particularly the lichens of the Kermadec Islands, Northland, Kaipara (Mataia), Waitakere Ranges, urban Auckland, Auckland Regional Parks, Hauraki Gulf Islands (notable collections from Rangitoto, Motukaikoura and Tiritirimatangi), Waikato and Chatham Islands. Herbarium collections also reflect participation in Auckland Bioblitz (Auckland Domain, Auckland Botanical Gardens, Dingle Dell, Kepa Bush/Pourewa, Miranda, Smiths Bush, and Twin Streams (Opanuku Stream Catchment)). Invasive plants are also well represented reflecting staff research interests and the courses taught by the facility.  The herbarium also holds DNA vouchers linked to the Applied Molecular Solutions Research Group (www.unitec.ac.nz/ams) and associated laboratory, and international lichen research consortia (PhyloRamalina, Lecanomics, Parsys).  The earliest collections are those donated collections from 1965 (Judy Nicholson, mainly South Island), with other later donations from the 1980s and 1990s, before active collecting began in 2001.  History: UNITEC was founded by Carol Elliott (nee Lockett) and Dan Blanchon in 2001. It is a teaching and research herbarium, supporting the research of an active lichen research group, as well as research on invasive and native species. Students learn herbarium specimen collection and preparation in three different courses in the Bachelor of Applied Science, and students volunteer in the herbarium to assist with accessioning and curation. The herbarium supports taxonomy education, particularly in lichenology, mycology, botany and biosecurity.  Key staff: Dr Peter de Lange, Dr Mark Large, Hayley Nessia, Andrew Marshall, Matt McClymont.

name: NA
citation: University of New Mexico Herbarium (UNM) (2019). University of New Mexico Herbarium. Occurrence dataset https://doi.org/10.15468/dlvoyt accessed via GBIF.org on 2019-12-11.
notes: We are pleased to announce the donation of the College of Santa Fe Herbarium to the UNM Herbarium in the Museum of Southwestern Biology, University of New Mexico. The collection includes over 1800 specimens of vascular plants and several hundred bryophytes, hepatics, and lichens, largely collected by Brother Arsène Brouard in the 1920's and 30's in New Mexico. Brother Arsène was the first collector to work extensively in northern New Mexico since the early botanical explorations in the 1840s by Gambel, Wislizenus, Emory, and Fendler. Wooten and Standley collected east of Santa Fe briefly in 1908. Arsène’s notes indicate that he collected at least 5,000 specimens in northern New Mexico, several thousand of which are at the Smithsonian and nearly 1800 are in the donated herbarium from The College of Santa Fe. There are also a number of specimens collected in Mexico by Brother Arsène. The specimens will not be available for study until they are curated and databased.

organization: Universidad Pedogógica y Tecnológica de Colombia
geography: Colombia, especially Boyacá and Eastern upland
notes: Updated Oct 2015.. The herbarium was created because of the need of professors and students of having an appropriate space for the investigation and of the study of flora in the state. In its start-up was directed by professor Rafael Guarin Montoya with the help of his auxiliary Mardoqueo Villarreal. In 1984 the management was in charge of professor Rafael Castillo.In 1998 he dismissed and only at the beginning of 1999 professor Maria Eugenia Morales Puentes took over the direction and she is still in charge of the herbarium UPTC. The UPTC herbarium is a collection of regional type, registered as a biological collection with scientific purposes before the institute Alexander Von Humboldt (number 26 under initial UPTC-H),According to legislation established by the Ministry of Environment in resolution number 1115 of year 2000 ,and it is considered National Patrimony, besides of being place of important reference of fauna an d flora from Boyaca ,although it includes areas from sates that share borders as Casanare and Santander. The herbarium has about 21,314 specimen and some vegetal collections among them the Briofitos collection(Mosses,Hepatics,Antoceros y Lichens), from Ferns and Licofitas of angioespermas from fruits and seeds(carpoteca) and a collection that has being created nowadays referred to vegetal fibers.The logo of the herbarium is represented through an illustration od Diplostephium jenesanum,a specie founded in the Boyaca State and it is described by the actual director and Santiago Diaz Piedrahita, sample type of the UPTC-H herbarium . Nowadays the herbarium is an active member of a variety of museums in Boyaca , its capital Tunja and of course of the university, besides it is member of Colombian association of herbariums(ACH) and has agreements with different public and private institutions in the country. The herbarium has a future projection as a unit where an important collection of plants from Boyaca and the Eastern Cordillera can be deposit, focused to services and problem solving, hypothesis, consulting, among others thesis, master degrees and PhD, visits to institutions (schools, universities and people interested in the matter)service of determination, drying and assembly of vegetal material, also we have a documentation center ,microscopy area, specialized software area (canopy l, leaves and seeds),cartographies, projection area, also we advise services related to Botany which are available to all the students and researchers.

department: 3rd Floor Research Center for the Natural and Applied Sciences
notes: Entered Aug 2016 (new curator). The UST Museum of Arts and Sciences was founded by a professor of Natural History, Fr. Ramon Martinez Vigil, O.P. in 1870 at Intramuros, Manila. With the efforts of Fr. Casto de Elera O.P., the natural sciences collections were scientifically classified and catalogued. Before World War II, the UST Museum of Arts and Sciences was transferred to its present site, at the UST Main Bldg., Sampaloc, Manila. In 1988, a large part of the plant collection composed of 8 herbarium cases of about 8,200 specimens were transferred to the Research Center for the Natural Sciences at the 4th floor, Clinical Division of the UST Hospital. Since then, the UST Herbarium is continuously being replenished with new specimens through the collections made by the UST RCNS research team, graduate and undergraduate students. With the completion of the Thomas Aquinas Research Complex in November 2001, the plant collections were moved to its new and modern location. The herbarium is equipped with modern facilities and an adjacent laboratory for herbarium curation.

exchange: Horticultural samples from the Washington Arboretum (Otis Douglas Hyde Herbarium duplicates)
notes: The UW Bothell Herbarium provides a critical authoritative record of plants occurring in the University of Washington Bothell and Cascadia College co-located campus wetland and the greater North Creek Basin. As the vegetation changes through time in the wetland it will form a reliable record to help us and future researchers understand biological and habitat change in one of our regions’ preeminent floodplain restoration projects. Collections focus on Snohomish and north King Counties, Washington, USA. It functions primarily as a teaching collection for undergraduate students, faculty, and researchers. It is open to the public by appointment.  The herbarium was founded in 2009 by Tyson Kemper, and 150 collections were added over the course of 7 years. In 2015, Sarah Verlinde started collecting as a student researcher. While collecting, she started a small volunteer team, and in the first year added another 100 specimens. In 2016, Sarah was hired full-time by the Office of Research (the herbarium sponsor), and continued to run the herbarium on a part-time basis. In three years, her team has added 750 more specimens. They joined an online consortium through the University of Washington herbarium at the Burke Museum (WTU) and now photograph and publish the specimens online at www.pnwherbaria.org.

notes: Entered Dec 2017. The Herbarium of Vietnamese Academy of Forest Sciences (VAFS) is one of the largest herbaria in North of Vietnam, with over 10.000 sheets of vascular plants from around Vietnam (major main wood trees and bamboos). Graduate and undergraduate students use herbarium material to identify plants and determine plant locations. Tours are conducted for numerous school groups, and other organizations. In addition, the collection grows steadily through local field work and donated material; and researchers at VAFS, especially those involved with floristic work, deposit their voucher sets for their projects at the Herbarium.

organization: Botanical Garden Dr. B.M. Kozo-Polyansky, Voronezh State University
notes: Entered Dec 2013. The specimens are used in the compilation of regional floras, for identification, as well as in the study of geography, ecology, biology, physiology of different species of plants. Thus, the herbarium materials are used in the refinement of the conservation status and geography of rare plant species as recommended in the Red Data Book of the Voronezh region. New specimens are being accessioned from the little-studied areas of the Central Black Soil and adjacent territories. Other areas of collection development include protected species, medicinal, food, and essential oil plants, as well as decorative plants. A database of the herbarium is in development.

name: NA
notes: Entered Jan 2016. Eastern Anatolia is the largest (approximately 170 000 km2) of seven geographical divisions of Turkey with 14 provinces, bordering Iraq, Iran, Nakhichevan, Armenia, and Georgia. It is included in the Irano-Turanian phytogeographical region, covered with deciduous-mixed forests and deciduous tree steppes. The area is surrounded by coastal mountain ranges, which protects it from the moderating effect of sea breezes. Subsequently, the winters are cold and long, with snow lasting for several months. They are followed by very short and rainy springs, and hot and dry summers. The mountainous and strongly fragmentised area offers numerous microclimatic and ecological zones, which provided suitable conditions for the development of diverse flora.  The local population has a comprehensive knowledge of traditional herbal medicines which are commonly used to prevent or to treat disease. This knowledge was developed over centuries, when Eastern Anatolia served as a passageway between the continents of Europe, Asia and Africa. A variety of flora, fauna and cultures owe their geographical spread to this passageway. Over many centuries a number of races and tribes originated from distant lands settled in Eastern Anatolia, bringing knowledge of plants and their various uses. This heritage, combined with the local flora, has contributed to an extensive use of plants in daily life as a medicine. The knowledge of herbal medicines in this region is still mostly passed on orally (with the exception of a few codices) from one generation of religious healers (referred to as‘seyh’) and local healers (‘hekim’) to the next.

exchange: Angiosperms of various areas, mainly of Europe and Mediterranean area; lichens worldwide; bryophytes of various areas
notes: Some specimens have been digitized, especially types, and records available in Virtual Herbaria: http://herbarium.univie.ac.at/database/search.php. Loan requests for type specimens must state exact details about place of publication, synonyms, type-locality, etc. Specimens are not arranged in geographical order, so general requests such as "all species of genus X from South America" cannot be accepted. Part of the phanerogam collection was destroyed by war accidents, corresponding to numbers 1-100, 452-1388, 1855-2828 of Dalla Torre & Harms, Genera Siphonogamarum (see Taxon 1: 29). Orchidaceae of H. G. L. Reichenbach and Juncaceae of F. G. T. Buchenau are not sent on loan. Attached to W are collections of fruits, seeds, and wood samples. About 180 000 botanical drawings and paintings (e.g., those of F. L. Bauer, N. J. and J. F. von Jacquin, C. A. A. Huegel, H. W. Schott, and H. G. Reichenbach) and botanical manuscripts and correspondence (e.g., letters to N. J. von Jacquin, S. L. Endlicher, H. G. L. and H. G. Reichenbach, and H. Lojka) are located in the Archives at the moment.

name: NA
organization: The Yugra State University Biological Collections
notes: Entered Mar 2016. The main goal of the YSU Biological Collection (YSU BC) is to accumulate biological collections and manage associated biodiversity information in the Khanty-Mansiyskiy Autonomous Okrug - Yugra. For that purpose, we are developing conditions for physical storage of samples, facilitating their scientific analysis, and applying computer technologies for storage, analysis and distribution of biodiversity data. We encourage researchers working in the area to share their biological collections with the YSU BC. A rule for the visitors of YSU Mukhrino field station was set since 2016 to share their collected material with the host university. We are working on development of online database of YSU BC in Specify 7 software. Currently it can be accessed for search of fungal collections at: http://bio.ugrasu.ru. The visitor login is: ugrabiodb; password: ugrabiodb.

name: NA
organization: Bryce Canyon National Park, Cedar Breaks National Monument, and Zion National Park
notes: Entered Apr 2016. Zion National Park manages a herbarium of over 3500 herbarium specimens. Zion also manages the herbaria from Cedar Breaks National Monument, over 900 specimens, and Bryce Canon National Monument, over 1800 specimens. These specimens provide baseline information about the natural environment of the three parks. These collections display the remarkable diversity at the convergence of three ecological provinces: the Colorado Plateau, the Great Basin, and the Mojave Desert. Zion’s collection represents over 95% of the confirmed 982 plant taxa in the park. The earliest specimens in the herbaria were collected in the 1920s with additions to the collection continuing today. Most of the specimens were collected from 1950s to 1980s.
